# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: louisville-baseball-park
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The **1877 Louisville Grays scandal** was an incident in which members of the Louisville Grays baseball team accepted money to lose games.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Four players – Bill Craver, Jim Devlin, George Hall and Al Nichols – were subsequently banned from professional baseball for life.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In the early days of professional baseball, crooked play was not uncommon, and many players were suspected of throwing games in exchange for money.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Illegal influence by gamblers had undermined the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA) in the early 1870s, and William Hulbert formed the National League (NL) in 1876 with the intention of driving it out of the game.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Nevertheless, there were still several gambling-related scandals during the 1876 season.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Jim Devlin started his baseball career in 1873 and was the Louisville Grays' pitcher in 1876 and 1877.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1876 he had a win–loss record of 30–35 and an earned run average of 1.56, while leading the league in complete games, innings pitched and strikeouts.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1877, Devlin went 35–25 with a 2.25 ERA and again led the league in complete games and innings pitched.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He started and completed each of the Grays' 61 games, an accomplishment no other pitcher in history has matched.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Outfielder George Hall was one of the best sluggers in the game's early history.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] After playing in the NA from 1871 to 1875, he joined the Philadelphia Athletics in 1876.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] That season, he led the league with five home runs and finished second in batting average, on-base percentage, slugging percentage and total bases.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1877, he played for the Grays and had a .323 batting average.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Shortstop Bill Craver was a noted crooked player who had been expelled from a previous team for throwing games in 1870.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He played for the New York Mutuals in 1876 before joining the Grays the following season.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Al Nichols also played for the Mutuals in 1876.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He joined the Grays in the middle of the 1877 season on the recommendation of Hall and appeared in six games for the team.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Newspapers named the players "Terror" Devlin, "Gentleman George" Hall, "Butcher" Craver and "Slippery Elm" Nichols".
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] After the games of August 13, 1877, the Grays were in first place by four games over St.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Louis and 4.5 over the Boston Red Caps, with a record of 27 wins and 13 losses, and with some 20 games left to play.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] They then commenced a nine-game winless streak (including one tie) and eventually lost the championship to Boston.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] They won six out of their last seven, making their season record of 35-25 look reasonably respectable, but those wins came after Boston had clinched the pennant, having won 20 of their final 21 games.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Louisville finished second, seven games behind Boston.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Chase received telegrams informing him of suspicious gambling activity involving the team.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He started an investigation, and Devlin and Hall confessed to throwing several exhibition games late in the season, with Devlin receiving up to $100 per game.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] On October 4, the entire team was gathered, and Chase demanded that they turn over their telegrams.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Every player except Craver complied, and the telegrams showed that Devlin, Hall and Nichols had thrown games.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] On October 30, Craver, Devlin, Hall and Nichols were expelled from the club, and on December 4, the NL banned them from professional baseball for the rest of their lives.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The Grays franchise folded after the 1877 season.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Over the next few decades, there were fewer suspicions of game-fixing in professional baseball.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The four banned players were never reinstated.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Nichols played semi-professional baseball, Craver and Devlin became police officers, and Hall worked as an engraver and clerk.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Devlin tried to be reinstated many times but was unsuccessful.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In one instance, he got on his knees and begged Hulbert for another chance.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Hulbert responded by handing him $50 (roughly equivalent to $1,200 in 2017 value) and saying, "Devlin, that's what I think of you personally; but, damn you, you have sold a game; you are dishonest and this National League will not stand for it." Devlin died of tuberculosis in 1883.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] His 1.90 career ERA is the third-lowest of all-time among pitchers with at least 1,000 innings pitched.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The initial objective of the batting team is to have a player reach first base safely; this occurs either when the batter hits the ball and reaches first base before an opponent retrieves the ball and touches the base, or when the pitcher persists in throwing the ball out of the batter's reach.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Players on the batting team who reach first base without being called "out" can attempt to advance to subsequent bases as a runner, either immediately or during teammates' turns batting.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The fielding team tries to prevent runs by using the ball to get batters or runners "out", which forces them out of the field of play.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The pitcher can get the batter out by throwing three pitches which result in strikes, while fielders can get the batter out by catching a batted ball before it touches the ground, and can get a runner out by tagging them with the ball while the runner is not touching a base.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The opposing teams switch back and forth between batting and fielding; the batting team's turn to bat is over once the fielding team records three outs.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] One turn batting for each team constitutes an inning.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A game is usually composed of nine innings, and the team with the greater number of runs at the end of the game wins.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Most games end after the ninth inning, but if scores are tied at that point, extra innings are usually played.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Baseball has no game clock, though some competitions feature pace-of-play regulations such as a pitch clock to shorten game time.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Baseball evolved from older bat-and-ball games already being played in England by the mid-18th century.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] This game was brought by immigrants to North America, where the modern version developed.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In addition to North America, baseball spread throughout the rest of the Americas and the Asia–Pacific in the 19th and 20th centuries, and is now considered the most popular sport in parts of Central and South America, the Caribbean, and East Asia, particularly in Japan, South Korea, and Taiwan.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In Major League Baseball (MLB), the highest level of professional baseball in the United States and Canada, teams are divided into the National League (NL) and American League (AL), each with three divisions: East, West, and Central.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The MLB champion is determined by playoffs that culminate in the World Series.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The top level of play is similarly split in Japan between the Central and Pacific Leagues and in Cuba between the West League and East League.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The World Baseball Classic, organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation, is the major international competition of the sport and attracts the top national teams from around the world.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Baseball was played at the Olympic Games from 1992 to 2008, and was reinstated on a one-off basis in 2020.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A baseball game is played between two teams, each composed of nine players, that take turns playing offense (batting and baserunning) and defense (pitching and fielding).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A pair of turns, one at bat and one in the field, by each team constitutes an inning.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A game consists of nine innings (seven innings at the high school level and in doubleheaders in college and Minor League Baseball; and six innings at the Little League level).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] One team—customarily the visiting team—bats in the top, or first half, of every inning.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The other team—customarily the home team—bats in the bottom, or second half, of every inning.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The goal of the game is to score more points (runs) than the other team.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The players on the team at bat attempt to score runs by touching all four bases, in order, set at the corners of the square-shaped baseball diamond.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A player bats at home plate and must attempt to safely reach a base before proceeding, counterclockwise, from first base, to second base, third base, and back home to score a run.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The team in the field attempts to prevent runs from scoring by recording outs, which remove opposing players from offensive action until their next turn at bat comes up again.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] When three outs are recorded, the teams switch roles for the next half-inning.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] If the score of the game is tied after nine innings, extra innings are played to resolve the contest.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Many amateur games, particularly unorganized ones, involve different numbers of players and innings.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The game is played on a field whose primary boundaries, the foul lines, extend forward from home plate at 45-degree angles.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The 90-degree area within the foul lines is referred to as fair territory; the 270-degree area outside them is foul territory.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The part of the field enclosed by the bases and several yards beyond them is the infield; the area farther beyond the infield is the outfield.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In the middle of the infield is a raised pitcher's mound, with a rectangular rubber plate (the rubber) at its center.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The outer boundary of the outfield is typically demarcated by a raised fence, which may be of any material and height.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The fair territory between home plate and the outfield boundary is baseball's field of play, though significant events can take place in foul territory, as well.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Protective helmets are also standard equipment for all batters.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] At the beginning of each half-inning, the nine players of the fielding team arrange themselves around the field.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] One of them, the pitcher, stands on the pitcher's mound.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The pitcher begins the pitching delivery with one foot on the rubber, pushing off it to gain velocity when throwing toward home plate.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Another fielding team player, the catcher, squats on the far side of home plate, facing the pitcher.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The rest of the fielding team faces home plate, typically arranged as four infielders—who set up along or within a few yards outside the imaginary lines (basepaths) between first, second, and third base—and three outfielders.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In the standard arrangement, there is a first baseman positioned several steps to the left of first base, a second baseman to the right of second base, a shortstop to the left of second base, and a third baseman to the right of third base.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The basic outfield positions are left fielder, center fielder, and right fielder.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] With the exception of the catcher, all fielders are required to be in fair territory when the pitch is delivered.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A neutral umpire sets up behind the catcher.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Other umpires will be distributed around the field as well.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Play starts with a member of the batting team, the batter, standing in either of the two batter's boxes next to home plate, holding a bat.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The batter waits for the pitcher to throw a pitch (the ball) toward home plate, and attempts to hit the ball with the bat.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The catcher catches pitches that the batter does not hit—as a result of either electing not to swing or failing to connect—and returns them to the pitcher.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A batter who hits the ball into the field of play must drop the bat and begin running toward first base, at which point the player is referred to as a *runner* (or, until the play is over, a *batter-runner*).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A batter-runner who reaches first base without being put out is said to be *safe* and is on base.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A batter-runner may choose to remain at first base or attempt to advance to second base or even beyond—however far the player believes can be reached safely.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base despite proper play by the fielders has recorded a hit.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A player who reaches first base safely on a hit is credited with a single.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] If a player makes it to second base safely as a direct result of a hit, it is a double; third base, a triple.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air within the foul lines over the entire outfield (and outfield fence, if there is one), or if the batter-runner otherwise safely circles all the bases, it is a home run: the batter and any runners on base may all freely circle the bases, each scoring a run.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] This is the most desirable result for the batter.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The ultimate and most desirable result possible for a batter would be to hit a home run while all three bases are occupied or "loaded", thus scoring four runs on a single hit.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base due to a fielding mistake is not credited with a hit—instead, the responsible fielder is charged with an error.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Any runners already on base may attempt to advance on batted balls that land, or contact the ground, in fair territory, before or after the ball lands.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A runner on first base *must* attempt to advance if a ball lands in play, as only one runner may occupy a base at any given time; the same applies for other runners if they are on a base that a teammate is forced to advance to.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] If a ball hit into play rolls foul before passing through the infield, it becomes dead and any runners must return to the base they occupied when the play began.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air and caught before it lands, the batter has flied out and any runners on base may attempt to advance only if they tag up (contact the base they occupied when the play began, as or after the ball is caught).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Runners may also attempt to advance to the next base while the pitcher is in the process of delivering the ball to home plate; a successful effort is a stolen base.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A pitch that is not hit into the field of play is called either a strike or a ball.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A batter against whom three strikes are recorded strikes out.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A batter against whom four balls are recorded is awarded a base on balls or walk, a free advance to first base.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] While the team at bat is trying to score runs, the team in the field is attempting to record outs.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In addition to the strikeout and flyout, common ways a member of the batting team may be put out include the ground out, force out, and tag out.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] These occur either when a runner is forced to advance to a base, and a fielder with possession of the ball reaches that base before the runner does, or the runner is touched by the ball, held in a fielder's hand, while not on a base.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] (The batter-runner is always forced to advance to first base, and any other runners must advance to the next base if a teammate is forced to advance to their base.) It is possible to record two outs in the course of the same play.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Three outs in one play, a triple play, is possible, though rare.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Players put out or retired must leave the field, returning to their team's dugout or bench.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A runner may be stranded on base when a third out is recorded against another player on the team.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Stranded runners do not benefit the team in its next turn at bat as every half-inning begins with the bases empty.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] An individual player's turn batting or plate appearance is complete when the player reaches base, hits a home run, makes an out, or hits a ball that results in the team's third out, even if it is recorded against a teammate.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] On rare occasions, a batter may be at the plate when, without the batter's hitting the ball, a third out is recorded against a teammate—for instance, a runner getting caught stealing (tagged out attempting to steal a base).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A batter with this sort of incomplete plate appearance starts off the team's next turn batting; any balls or strikes recorded against the batter the previous inning are erased.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A runner may circle the bases only once per plate appearance and thus can score at most a single run per batting turn.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Once a player has completed a plate appearance, that player may not bat again until the eight other members of the player's team have all taken their turn at bat in the batting order.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The batting order is set before the game begins, and may not be altered except for substitutions.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Once a player has been removed for a substitute, that player may not reenter the game.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Children's games often have more lenient rules, such as Little League rules, which allow players to be substituted back into the same game.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] If the designated hitter (DH) rule is in effect, each team has a tenth player whose sole responsibility is to bat (and run).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The DH takes the place of another player—almost invariably the pitcher—in the batting order, but does not field.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Thus, even with the DH, each team still has a batting order of nine players and a fielding arrangement of nine players.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The number of players on a baseball roster, or *squad*, varies by league and by the level of organized play.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A Major League Baseball (MLB) team has a roster of 26 players with specific roles.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Most baseball leagues worldwide have the DH rule, including MLB, Japan's Pacific League, and Caribbean professional leagues, along with major American amateur organizations.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The Central League in Japan does not have the rule and high-level minor league clubs connected to National League teams are not required to field a DH.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In leagues that apply the designated hitter rule, a typical team has nine offensive regulars (including the DH), five starting pitchers, seven or eight relievers, a backup catcher, and two or three other reserve players.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The manager, or head coach, oversees the team's major strategic decisions, such as establishing the starting rotation, setting the lineup, or batting order, before each game, and making substitutions during games—in particular, bringing in relief pitchers.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Managers are typically assisted by two or more coaches; they may have specialized responsibilities, such as working with players on hitting, fielding, pitching, or strength and conditioning.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] At most levels of organized play, two coaches are stationed on the field when the team is at bat: the first base coach and third base coach, who occupy designated coaches' boxes, just outside the foul lines.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] These coaches assist in the direction of baserunners, when the ball is in play, and relay tactical signals from the manager to batters and runners, during pauses in play.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In contrast to many other team sports, baseball managers and coaches generally wear their team's uniforms; coaches must be in uniform to be allowed on the field to confer with players during a game.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Any baseball game involves one or more umpires, who make rulings on the outcome of each play.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] At a minimum, one umpire will stand behind the catcher, to have a good view of the strike zone, and call balls and strikes.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Additional umpires may be stationed near the other bases, thus making it easier to judge plays such as attempted force outs and tag outs.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In MLB, four umpires are used for each game, one near each base.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In the playoffs, six umpires are used: one at each base and two in the outfield along the foul lines.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Many of the pre-game and in-game strategic decisions in baseball revolve around a fundamental fact: in general, right-handed batters tend to be more successful against left-handed pitchers and, to an even greater degree, left-handed batters tend to be more successful against right-handed pitchers.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A manager with several left-handed batters in the regular lineup, who knows the team will be facing a left-handed starting pitcher, may respond by starting one or more of the right-handed backups on the team's roster.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] During the late innings of a game, as relief pitchers and pinch hitters are brought in, the opposing managers will often go back and forth trying to create favorable matchups with their substitutions.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The manager of the fielding team trying to arrange same-handed pitcher-batter matchups and the manager of the batting team trying to arrange opposite-handed matchups.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] With a team that has the lead in the late innings, a manager may remove a starting position player—especially one whose turn at bat is not likely to come up again—for a more skillful fielder (known as a defensive substitution).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The tactical decision that precedes almost every play in a baseball game involves pitch selection.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] By gripping and then releasing the baseball in a certain manner, and by throwing it at a certain speed, pitchers can cause the baseball to break to either side, or downward, as it approaches the batter, thus creating differing pitches that can be selected.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Among the resulting wide variety of pitches that may be thrown, the four basic types are the fastball, the changeup (or off-speed pitch), and two breaking balls—the curveball and the slider.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Pitchers have different repertoires of pitches they are skillful at throwing.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Conventionally, before each pitch, the catcher signals the pitcher what type of pitch to throw, as well as its general vertical or horizontal location.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] If there is disagreement on the selection, the pitcher may shake off the sign and the catcher will call for a different pitch.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] With a runner on base and taking a lead, the pitcher may attempt a pickoff, a quick throw to a fielder covering the base to keep the runner's lead in check or, optimally, effect a tag out.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Pickoff attempts, however, are subject to rules that severely restrict the pitcher's movements before and during the pickoff attempt.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Violation of any one of these rules could result in the umpire calling a balk against the pitcher, which permits any runners on base to advance one base with impunity.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] If an attempted stolen base is anticipated, the catcher may call for a pitchout, a ball thrown deliberately off the plate, allowing the catcher to catch it while standing and throw quickly to a base.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Facing a batter with a strong tendency to hit to one side of the field, the fielding team may employ a shift, with most or all of the fielders moving to the left or right of their usual positions.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] With a runner on third base, the infielders may play in, moving closer to home plate to improve the odds of throwing out the runner on a ground ball, though a sharply hit grounder is more likely to carry through a drawn-in infield.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Several basic offensive tactics come into play with a runner on first base, including the fundamental choice of whether to attempt a steal of second base.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The hit and run is sometimes employed, with a skillful contact hitter, the runner takes off with the pitch, drawing the shortstop or second baseman over to second base, creating a gap in the infield for the batter to poke the ball through.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The sacrifice bunt, calls for the batter to focus on making soft contact with the ball, so that it rolls a short distance into the infield, allowing the runner to advance into scoring position as the batter is thrown out at first.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A batter, particularly one who is a fast runner, may also attempt to bunt for a hit.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A sacrifice bunt employed with a runner on third base, aimed at bringing that runner home, is known as a squeeze play.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] With a runner on third and fewer than two outs, a batter may instead concentrate on hitting a fly ball that, even if it is caught, will be deep enough to allow the runner to tag up and score—a successful batter, in this case, gets credit for a sacrifice fly.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In order to increase the chance of advancing a batter to first base via a walk, the manager will sometimes signal a batter who is ahead in the count (i.e., has more balls than strikes) to take, or not swing at, the next pitch.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The batter's potential reward of reaching base (via a walk) exceeds the disadvantage if the next pitch is a strike.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Consensus once held that today's baseball is a North American development from the older game rounders, popular among children in Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] American baseball historian David Block suggests that the game originated in England; recently uncovered historical evidence supports this position.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] According to Block and official MLB historian John Thorn, this earlier version of baseball may have involved hitting the ball with a hand, making it akin to today's punchball.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Block argues that rounders and early baseball were actually regional variants of each other, and that the game's most direct antecedents are the English games of stoolball and "tut-ball".
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The earliest known reference to baseball is in a 1744 British publication, *A Little Pretty Pocket-Book*, by John Newbery.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Block discovered that the first recorded game of "Base Ball" took place in 1749 in Surrey, and featured the Prince of Wales as a player.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] This early form of the game was apparently brought to Canada by English immigrants.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] By the early 1830s, there were reports of a variety of uncodified bat-and-ball games recognizable as early forms of baseball being played around North America.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The first recorded baseball game in North America was played in Beachville, Ontario, Canada, on June 4, 1838.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In 1845, Alexander Cartwright, a member of New York City's Knickerbocker Club, led the codification of the so-called Knickerbocker Rules, which in turn were based on rules developed in 1837 by William R.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] While there are reports that the New York Knickerbockers played games in 1845, the contest long recognized as the first recorded baseball game in U.S. history took place on June 19, 1846, in Hoboken, New Jersey: the "New York Nine" defeated the Knickerbockers, 23–1, in four innings.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] With the Knickerbocker code as the basis, the rules of modern baseball continued to evolve over the next half-century.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The game then went on to spread throughout the Pacific Rim and the Americas, with Americans backing the sport as a way to spread American values.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In the mid-1850s, a baseball craze hit the New York metropolitan area, and by 1856, local journals were referring to baseball as the "national pastime" or "national game".
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A year later, the sport's first governing body, the National Association of Base Ball Players, was formed.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In 1867, it barred participation by African Americans.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The more formally structured National League was founded in 1876.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Professional Negro leagues formed, but quickly folded.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In 1887, softball, under the name of indoor baseball or indoor-outdoor, was invented as a winter version of the parent game.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The American League evolved from the minor Western League, which was reorganized under Ban Johnson in 1893.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] It was not until 1901 that the American League was formally established as a major league.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] By 1893, crucial structural changes (like moving the pitching distance to 60 feet, 6 inches) firmly cemented the modern rulebook.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The National Agreement of 1903 formalized relations both between the two major leagues and between them and the National Association of Professional Base Ball Leagues, representing most of the country's minor professional leagues.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The World Series, pitting the two major league champions against each other, was inaugurated that fall.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The Black Sox Scandal of the 1919 World Series led to the formation of the office of the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The first commissioner, Kenesaw Mountain Landis, was elected in 1920.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] That year also saw the founding of the Negro National League; the first significant Negro league, it would operate until 1931.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] For part of the 1920s, it was joined by the Eastern Colored League.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Compared with the present, professional baseball in the early 20th century was lower-scoring, and pitchers were more dominant.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] This so-called "dead-ball era" ended in the early 1920s with several changes in rule and circumstance that were advantageous to hitters.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Strict new regulations that governed the ball's size, shape and composition, along with a new rule officially banning the spitball and other pitches that depended on the ball being treated or roughed-up with foreign substances, resulted in a ball that traveled farther when hit.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The rise of the legendary player Babe Ruth, the first great power hitter of the new era, helped permanently alter the nature of the game.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Louis Cardinals general manager Branch Rickey invested in several minor league clubs and developed the first modern farm system.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A new Negro National League was organized in 1933; four years later, it was joined by the Negro American League.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The first elections to the National Baseball Hall of Fame took place in 1936.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In 1939, Little League Baseball was founded in Pennsylvania.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Many minor league teams disbanded when World War II led to a player shortage.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Wrigley led the formation of the All-American Girls Professional Baseball League to help keep the game in the public eye.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The first crack in the unwritten agreement barring blacks from white-controlled professional ball occurred in 1945: Jackie Robinson was signed by the National League's Brooklyn Dodgers and began playing for their minor league team in Montreal.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In 1947, Robinson broke the major leagues' color barrier when he debuted with the Dodgers.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Latin-American players, largely overlooked before, also started entering the majors in greater numbers.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In 1951, two Chicago White Sox, Venezuelan-born Chico Carrasquel and black Cuban-born Minnie Miñoso, became the first Hispanic All-Stars.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Integration proceeded slowly: by 1953, only six of the 16 major league teams had a black player on the roster.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In 1975, the union's power—and players' salaries—began to increase greatly when the reserve clause was effectively struck down, leading to the free agency system.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Significant work stoppages occurred in 1981 and 1994, the latter forcing the cancellation of the World Series for the first time in 90 years.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Attendance had been growing steadily since the mid-1970s and in 1994, before the stoppage, the majors were setting their all-time record for per-game attendance.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] After play resumed in 1995, non-division-winning wild card teams became a permanent fixture of the post-season.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Regular-season interleague play was introduced in 1997 and the second-highest attendance mark for a full season was set.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In 2000, the National and American Leagues were dissolved as legal entities.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] While their identities were maintained for scheduling purposes (and the designated hitter distinction), the regulations and other functions—such as player discipline and umpire supervision—they had administered separately were consolidated under the rubric of MLB.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In 2001, Barry Bonds established the current record of 73 home runs in a single season.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In 2007, Bonds became MLB's all-time home run leader, surpassing Hank Aaron, as total major league and minor league attendance both reached all-time highs.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Despite having been called "America's national pastime", baseball is well-established in several other countries.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] As early as 1877, a professional league, the International Association, featured teams from both Canada and the United States.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] While baseball is widely played in Canada and many minor league teams have been based in the country, the American major leagues did not include a Canadian club until 1969, when the Montreal Expos joined the National League as an expansion team.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In 1977, the expansion Toronto Blue Jays joined the American League.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In 1847, American soldiers played what may have been the first baseball game in Mexico at Parque Los Berros in Xalapa, Veracruz.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The first formal baseball league outside of the United States and Canada was founded in 1878 in Cuba, which maintains a rich baseball tradition.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The English football club, Aston Villa, were the first British baseball champions winning the 1890 National League of Baseball of Great Britain.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The 2025 National Champions were the London Mets.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The Dominican Republic held its first islandwide championship tournament in 1912.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Professional baseball tournaments and leagues began to form in other countries between the world wars, including the Netherlands (formed in 1922), Australia (1934), Japan (1936), Mexico (1937), and Puerto Rico (1938).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The Japanese major leagues have long been considered the highest quality professional circuits outside of the United States.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] After World War II, professional leagues were founded in many Latin American countries, most prominently Venezuela (1946) and the Dominican Republic (1955).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Since the early 1970s, the annual Caribbean Series has matched the championship clubs from the four leading Latin American winter leagues: the Dominican Professional Baseball League, Mexican Pacific League, Puerto Rican Professional Baseball League, and Venezuelan Professional Baseball League.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In Asia, South Korea (1982), Taiwan (1990) and China (2003) all have professional leagues.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Other European countries have seen professional leagues; the most successful, other than the Dutch league, is the Italian league, founded in 1948.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In 2004, Australia won a surprise silver medal at the Olympic Games.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The Confédération Européene de Baseball (European Baseball Confederation), founded in 1953, organizes a number of competitions between clubs from different countries.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Women's baseball is played on an organized amateur basis in numerous countries.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] After being admitted to the Olympics as a medal sport beginning with the 1992 Games, baseball was dropped from the 2012 Summer Olympic Games at the 2005 International Olympic Committee meeting.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] While the sport's lack of a following in much of the world was a factor, more important was MLB's reluctance to allow its players to participate during the major league season.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] MLB initiated the World Baseball Classic, scheduled to precede its season, partly as a replacement, high-profile international tournament.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The inaugural Classic, held in March 2006, was the first tournament involving national teams to feature a significant number of MLB participants.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The Baseball World Cup was discontinued after its 2011 edition in favor of an expanded World Baseball Classic.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Baseball has certain attributes that set it apart from the other popular team sports in the countries where it has a following.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] All of these sports use a clock, play is less individual, and the variation between playing fields is not as substantial or important.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The comparison between cricket and baseball demonstrates that many of baseball's distinctive elements are shared in various ways with similar sports.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In clock-limited sports, games often end with a team that holds the lead killing the clock rather than competing aggressively against the opposing team.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In contrast, baseball has no clock, thus a team cannot win without getting the last batter out and rallies are not constrained by time.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] At almost any turn in any baseball game, the most advantageous strategy is some form of aggressive strategy.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] While nine innings has been the standard since the beginning of professional baseball, the duration of the average major league game has increased steadily through the years.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] At the turn of the 20th century, games typically took an hour and a half to play.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In the 1920s, they averaged just less than two hours, which eventually ballooned to 2:38 in 1960.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] By 1997, the average American League game lasted 2:57 (National League games were about 10 minutes shorter—pitchers at the plate making for quicker outs than designated hitters).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In 2004, Major League Baseball declared that its goal was an average game of 2:45.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] By 2014, though, the average MLB game took over three hours to complete.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The lengthening of games is attributed to longer breaks between half-innings for television commercials, increased offense, more pitching changes, and a slower pace of play, with pitchers taking more time between each delivery, and batters stepping out of the box more frequently.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Other leagues have experienced similar issues.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In 2008, Nippon Professional Baseball took steps aimed at shortening games by 12 minutes from the preceding decade's average of 3:18.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In 2016, the average nine-inning playoff game in Major League baseball was 3 hours and 35 minutes.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] This was up 10 minutes from 2015 and 21 minutes from 2014.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In response to the lengthening of the game, MLB decided from the 2023 season onward to institute a pitch clock rule to penalize batters and pitchers who take too much time between pitches; this had the effect of shortening 2023 regular season games by 24 minutes on average.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Although baseball is a team sport, individual players are often placed under scrutiny and pressure.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] While rewarding, it has sometimes been described as "ruthless" due to the pressure on the individual player.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] In 1915, a baseball instructional manual pointed out that every single pitch, of which there are often more than two hundred in a game, involves an individual, one-on-one contest: "the pitcher and the batter in a battle of wits".
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Pitcher, batter, and fielder all act essentially independent of each other.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] While coaching staffs can signal pitcher or batter to pursue certain tactics, the execution of the play itself is a series of solitary acts.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] If the batter hits a line drive, the outfielder is solely responsible for deciding to try to catch it or play it on the bounce and for succeeding or failing.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The statistical precision of baseball is both facilitated by this isolation and reinforces it.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] There is no statistical equivalent in cricket for the fielding error and thus less emphasis on personal responsibility in this area of play.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Unlike those of most sports, baseball playing fields can vary significantly in size and shape.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Major league teams often skirt even this rule.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] For example, at Daikin Park, which became the home of the Houston Astros in 2000, the Crawford Boxes in left field are only 315 feet (96 m) from home plate.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] There are no rules at all that address the height of fences or other structures at the edge of the outfield.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The most famously idiosyncratic outfield boundary is the left-field wall at Boston's Fenway Park, in use since 1912: the Green Monster is 310 feet (94 m) from home plate down the line and 37 feet (11 m) tall.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Similarly, there are no regulations at all concerning the dimensions of foul territory.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Thus a foul fly ball may be entirely out of play in a park with little space between the foul lines and the stands, but a foulout in a park with more expansive foul ground.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A fence in foul territory that is close to the outfield line will tend to direct balls that strike it back toward the fielders, while one that is farther away may actually prompt more collisions, as outfielders run full speed to field balls deep in the corner.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] These variations can make the difference between a double and a triple or inside-the-park home run.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The surface of the field is also unregulated.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] While the adjacent image shows a traditional field surfacing arrangement (and the one used by virtually all MLB teams with naturally surfaced fields), teams are free to decide what areas will be grassed or bare.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Some fields—including several in MLB—use artificial turf.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Surface variations can have a significant effect on how ground balls behave and are fielded as well as on baserunning.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Similarly, the presence of a roof (seven major league teams play in stadiums with permanent or retractable roofs) can greatly affect how fly balls are played.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] While football and soccer players deal with similar variations of field surface and stadium covering, the size and shape of their fields are much more standardized.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The area out-of-bounds on a football or soccer field does not affect play the way foul territory in baseball does, so variations in that regard are largely insignificant.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] These physical variations create a distinctive set of playing conditions at each ballpark.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Other local factors, such as altitude and climate, can also significantly affect play.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A given stadium may acquire a reputation as a pitcher's park or a hitter's park, if one or the other discipline notably benefits from its unique mix of elements.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The most exceptional park in this regard is Coors Field, home of the Colorado Rockies.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Its high altitude—5,282 feet (1,610 m) above sea level—is partly responsible for giving it the strongest hitter's park effect in the major leagues due to the low air pressure.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] Wrigley Field, home of the Chicago Cubs, is known for its fickle disposition: a pitcher's park when the strong winds off Lake Michigan are blowing in, it becomes more of a hitter's park when they are blowing out.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] The absence of a standardized field affects not only how particular games play out, but the nature of team rosters and players' statistical records.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] For example, hitting a fly ball 330 feet (100 m) into right field might result in an easy catch on the warning track at one park, and a home run at another.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] A team that plays in a park with a relatively short right field, such as the New York Yankees, will tend to stock its roster with left-handed pull hitters, who can best exploit it.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p01] On the individual level, a player who spends most of his career with a team that plays in a hitter's park will gain an advantage in batting statistics over time—even more so if his talents are especially suited to the park.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Organized baseball lends itself to statistics to a greater degree than many other sports.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Each play is discrete and has a relatively small number of possible outcomes.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] The Official Baseball Rules administered by MLB require the official scorer to categorize each baseball play unambiguously.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] The rules provide detailed criteria to promote consistency.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] The score report is the official basis for both the box score of the game and the relevant statistical records.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] General managers, managers, and baseball scouts use statistics to evaluate players and make strategic decisions.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Certain traditional statistics are familiar to most baseball fans.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Among the many other statistics that are kept are those collectively known as *situational statistics*.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] For example, statistics can indicate which specific pitchers a certain batter performs best against.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] If a given situation statistically favors a certain batter, the manager of the fielding team may be more likely to change pitchers or have the pitcher intentionally walk the batter in order to face one who is less likely to succeed.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Sabermetrics is the field of baseball statistical study and the development of new statistics and analytical tools.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Such new statistics are also called sabermetrics.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] The term was coined around 1980 by one of the field's leading proponents, Bill James, and derives from the Society for American Baseball Research (SABR).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Writing in 1919, philosopher Morris Raphael Cohen described baseball as the national religion of the US.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] In the words of sports columnist Jayson Stark, baseball has long been "a unique paragon of American culture"—a status he sees as devastated by the steroid abuse scandal.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] American influence in the Western Hemisphere has meant that baseball grew significantly in the region.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] A century later, the situation was very different.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] With the rise in popularity of other team sports with much higher average ticket prices—football, basketball, and hockey—professional baseball had become among the most popular blue-collar-oriented American spectator sports.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Overall, baseball has a large following in the United States; a 2006 poll found that nearly half of Americans are fans.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] This led to baseball being granted the title of "America's favorite pastime" by many American baseball fans.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] As historians and scholars now speculate, baseball is a metaphor of the American way of life In the late 1900s and early 2000s, baseball's position compared to football in the United States moved in contradictory directions.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] In 2008, MLB set a revenue record of $6.5 billion, matching the NFL's revenue for the first time in decades.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] A new MLB revenue record of more than $10 billion was set in 2017.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] On the other hand, the percentage of American sports fans polled who named baseball as their favorite sport was 9%, compared to pro football at 37%.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] In 1985, the respective figures were pro football 24%, baseball 23%.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Because there are so many more major league games played, there is no comparison in overall attendance.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] In 2008, total attendance at major league games was the second-highest in history: 78.6 million, 0.7% off the record set the previous year.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] The following year, amid the U.S. recession, attendance fell by 6.6% to 73.4 million.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Eight years later, it dropped under 73 million.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Attendance at games held under the Minor League Baseball umbrella set a record in 2008, with 43.3 million.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] While MLB games have not drawn the same national TV viewership as football games, MLB games are dominant in teams' local markets and regularly lead all programs in primetime in their markets during the summer.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] After multiple years of declines since 2017, baseball attendance has grown slightly in recent years.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] In 2024, attendance was 71.3 million, the highest since 2017.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Baseball is very popular in Venezuela; in 2011, 95% of people surveyed claimed it to be the national sport.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] In Nicaragua and Panama, baseball is also considered the national sport.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] While soccer is still more popular, baseball is a fast-growing sport in Mexico.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] In 2024, top Mexican League baseball teams outdraw some Liga MX teams in attendance.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Baseball also is somewhat popular in Colombia, though secondary to soccer, especially in coastal areas such as Barranquilla and Cartagena which are near the Caribbean.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] In recent years, baseball has grown in popularity in Colombia, especially in the capital of Bogotá, due an increase of Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] In Brazil, baseball fan popularity has grown in the last few years, thanks to MLB broadcasts in Brazilian ESPN and the historic silver medal in 2023 Pan-American games.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] However, it still lags behind basketball and American football in the list of most played sports in Brazil.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Baseball has also grown in popularity in Argentina and Peru in recent years due to Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Costa Rica has also seen a growth in the popularity of baseball.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Since 1987, baseballs have exclusively been made in the Costa Rican town of Turrialba.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] In recent years, Major leaguer Mauricio Dubón has made efforts to increase support for the sport in the country.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] The sport's overall popularity in Latin America has assisted in integrating Latin American migrants to the United States.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Since the early 1980s, the Dominican Republic, in particular the city of San Pedro de Macorís, has been the major leagues' primary source of foreign talent.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] In 2017, 83 of the 868 players on MLB Opening Day rosters (and disabled lists) were from the country.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Among other Caribbean countries and territories, a combined 97 MLB players were born in Venezuela, Cuba, and Puerto Rico.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Hall-of-Famer Roberto Clemente remains one of the greatest national heroes in Puerto Rico's history.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] While baseball has long been the island's primary athletic pastime, its once well-attended professional winter league has declined in popularity since 1990, when young Puerto Rican players began to be included in the major leagues' annual first-year player draft.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] In Cuba, where baseball is by every reckoning the national sport, the national team overshadows the city and provincial teams that play in the top-level domestic leagues.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Baseball is also one of the most popular sports of Aruba and Curaçao, and a growing sport in The Bahamas and the US Virgin Islands.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] In East Asia, baseball is among the most popular sports in Japan, Taiwan and South Korea.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] In Japan, where baseball is inarguably the leading spectator team sport, combined revenue for the twelve teams in Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the body that oversees both the Central and Pacific Leagues, was estimated at $1 billion in 2007.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Total NPB attendance for the year was approximately 20 million.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] While in the preceding two decades, MLB attendance grew by 50 percent and revenue nearly tripled, the comparable NPB figures were stagnant.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] There are concerns that MLB's growing interest in acquiring star Japanese players will hurt the game in their home country.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Revenue figures are not released for the country's amateur system.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Similarly, according to one official pronouncement, the sport's governing authority "has never taken into account attendance ... because its greatest interest has always been the development of athletes".
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] In Taiwan, baseball is one of the most widely spectated sports, in TV and person.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown significantly in China in recent years, with MLB estimating in 2019 that there are 21 million active fans in the country.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Baseball was considered a national pastime in the Philippines in the 1960s and 70s, but the sport has since declined in popularity.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Since 2005, there have been efforts to revitalize the sport in the country.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Baseball saw a surge in popularity in Thailand following the countries' silver medal in baseball in the 2025 SEA Games, which were hosted in Thailand.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Baseball is generally a niche sport in Europe.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] However, baseball is somewhat popular in the Netherlands, where it is known as *honkbal*, thanks to influence from the United States after World War II and the Kingdoms control over Aruba and Curaçao where it is the most popular sport.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Baseball is also somewhat popular in portions of Italy, especially in the town of Nettuno, due to influence from American soldiers after World War II.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown in recent years in the Czech Republic, due in part to the Czech teams' success in the 2023 World Baseball Classic.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Baseball is one of the most popular sports in Palau and Guam.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] In Australia, baseball is a niche sport but the country does have a professional league.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Because the league is played in winter for the western hemisphere, it attracts American and Korean professional players looking to play winter league baseball.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] In 2026, there were more than 30 Australians playing college baseball in the United States compared to six in 2020.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] The Dodgers operate a large baseball academy in Mpigi, Uganda, and there are also baseball programs in Luwero, Uganda.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] There is also a Africa Baseball Academy in Nairobi, Nigeria.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Baseball was popular in South Africa prior to World War 2 but popularity has since waned.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] There are still teams and attempts to raise the popularity of baseball in the country, including the introduction of Baseball5.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] There is a growing baseball program in South Sudan, which has resulted in professional contracts.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] The Japan-Africa Baseball & Softball Foundation has created Koshien high school baseball tournaments in Tanzania, Ghana and Kenya, which Tanzania being the most successful.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] There are further plans for similar tournaments in Nigeria, South Sudan, Benin, Cameroon and Zambia.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] As of 2024, Little League Baseball oversees leagues with 2 million participants in more than 80 countries.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] The number of players has fallen since the 1990s, when 3 million children took part in Little League Baseball annually.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Babe Ruth League teams have over 1 million participants.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] According to the president of the International Baseball Federation in 2009, between 300,000 and 500,000 women and girls play baseball around the world, including Little League and the introductory game of Tee Ball.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] A varsity baseball team is an established part of physical education departments at most high schools and colleges in the United States.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] In 2015, nearly half a million high schoolers and over 34,000 collegians played on their schools' baseball teams.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] By early in the 20th century, intercollegiate baseball was Japan's leading sport.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Today, high school baseball in particular is immensely popular there.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] The final rounds of the two annual tournaments—the National High School Baseball Invitational Tournament in the spring, and the even more important National High School Baseball Championship in the summer—are broadcast around the country.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] The tournaments are known, respectively, as Spring Koshien and Summer Koshien after the 55,000-capacity stadium where they are played.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] In Cuba, baseball is a mandatory part of the state system of physical education, which begins at age six.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Talented children as young as seven are sent to special district schools for more intensive training—the first step on a ladder whose acme is the national baseball team.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Baseball has had a broad impact on popular culture, both in the United States and elsewhere.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Dozens of English-language idioms have been derived from baseball; in particular, the game is the source of a number of widely used sexual euphemisms.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] The first networked radio broadcasts in North America were of the 1922 World Series: famed sportswriter Grantland Rice announced play-by-play from New York City's Polo Grounds on WJZ–Newark, New Jersey, which was connected by wire to WGY–Schenectady, New York, and WBZ–Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] The baseball cap has become a ubiquitous fashion item not only in the United States and Japan, but also in countries where the sport itself is not particularly popular, such as the United Kingdom.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Baseball has inspired many works of art and entertainment.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] There have been many baseball movies, including the Academy Award–winning *The Pride of the Yankees* (1942) and the Oscar nominees *The Natural* (1984) and *Field of Dreams* (1989).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] The American Film Institute's selection of the ten best sports movies includes *The Pride of the Yankees* at number 3 and *Bull Durham* (1988) at number 5.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Baseball has provided thematic material for hits on both stage—the Adler–Ross musical *Damn Yankees*—and record—George J.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Gaskin's "Slide, Kelly, Slide", Simon and Garfunkel's "Mrs.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Robinson", and John Fogerty's "Centerfield".
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] The baseball-inspired comedic sketch "Who's on First?", popularized by Abbott and Costello in 1938, quickly became famous; six decades later, *Time* named it the best comedy routine of the 20th century.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Literary works connected to the game include the short fiction of Ring Lardner and novels such as Bernard Malamud's *The Natural* (the source for the movie), Robert Coover's *The Universal Baseball Association, Inc., J.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Henry Waugh, Prop.*, John Grisham's Calico Joe and W.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Kinsella's *Shoeless Joe* (the source for *Field of Dreams*).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Baseball's literary canon also includes the beat reportage of Damon Runyon; the columns of Grantland Rice, Red Smith, Dick Young, and Peter Gammons; and the essays of Roger Angell.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Among the celebrated nonfiction books in the field are Lawrence S.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Ritter's *The Glory of Their Times*, Roger Kahn's *The Boys of Summer*, and Michael Lewis's *Moneyball*.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] The 1970 publication of major league pitcher Jim Bouton's tell-all chronicle *Ball Four* is considered a turning point in the reporting of professional sports.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Baseball has also inspired the creation of new cultural forms.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Baseball cards were introduced in the late 19th century as trade cards.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] A typical example featured an image of a baseball player on one side and advertising for a business on the other.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] In the early 1900s they were produced widely as promotional items by tobacco and confectionery companies.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] The 1930s saw the popularization of the modern style of baseball card, with a player photograph accompanied on the rear by statistics and biographical data.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Baseball cards—many of which are now prized collectibles—are the source of the much broader trading card industry, involving similar products for different sports and non-sports-related fields.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Modern fantasy sports began in 1980 with the invention of Rotisserie League Baseball by New York writer Daniel Okrent and several friends.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Participants in a Rotisserie league draft notional teams from the list of active MLB players and play out an entire imaginary season with game outcomes based on the players' latest real-world statistics.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Rotisserie-style play quickly became a phenomenon.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Now known more generically as fantasy baseball, it has inspired similar games based on an array of different sports.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] The field boomed with increasing Internet access and new fantasy sports-related websites.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] By 2008, 29.9 million people in the United States and Canada were playing fantasy sports, spending $800 million on the hobby.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] The burgeoning popularity of fantasy baseball is also credited with the increasing attention paid to sabermetrics—first among fans, only later among baseball professionals.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Informal variations of baseball have popped up over time, with games like corkball reflecting local traditions and allowing the game to be played in diverse environments.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Two variations of baseball, softball and Baseball5, are internationally governed alongside baseball by the World Baseball Softball Confederation.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] American professional baseball teams toured Britain in 1874 and 1889, and had a great effect on similar sports in Britain.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] In Wales and Merseyside, a strong community game had already developed with skills and plays more in keeping with the American game and the Welsh began to informally adopt the name "baseball" (Pêl Fas), to reflect the American style.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] By the 1890s, calls were made to follow the success of other working class sports (like Rugby in Wales and Soccer in Merseyside) and adopt a distinct set of rules and bureaucracy.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] During the 1892 season rules for the game of "baseball" were agreed and the game was officially codified.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] Finnish baseball, also known as pesäpallo, is a combination of traditional ball-batting team games and North American baseball, invented by Lauri "Tahko" Pihkala in the 1920s.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] The basic idea of pesäpallo is similar to that of baseball: the offense tries to score by hitting the ball successfully and running through the bases, while the defense tries to put the batter and runners out.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] One of the most important differences between pesäpallo and baseball is that the ball is pitched vertically, which makes hitting the ball, as well as controlling the power and direction of the hit, much easier.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/baseball-p02] This gives the offensive game more variety, speed, and tactical aspects compared to baseball.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] A **geographic coordinate system** (**GCS**) is a spherical or geodetic coordinate system for measuring and communicating positions directly on Earth as latitude and longitude.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] It is the simplest, oldest, and most widely used type of the various spatial reference systems that are in use, and forms the basis for most others.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] Although latitude and longitude form a coordinate tuple like a Cartesian coordinate system, geographic coordinate systems are not Cartesian because the measurements are angles and are not on a planar surface.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] A full GCS specification, such as those listed in the EPSG and ISO 19111 standards, also includes a choice of geodetic datum (including an Earth ellipsoid), as different datums will yield different latitude and longitude values for the same location.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] The invention of a geographic coordinate system is generally credited to Eratosthenes of Cyrene, who composed his now-lost *Geography* at the Library of Alexandria in the 3rd century BC.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] A century later, Hipparchus of Nicaea improved on this system by determining latitude from stellar measurements rather than solar altitude and determining longitude by timings of lunar eclipses, rather than dead reckoning.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] Ptolemy credited him with the full adoption of longitude and latitude, rather than measuring latitude in terms of the length of the midsummer day.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] Ptolemy's 2nd-century *Geography* used the same prime meridian but measured latitude from the Equator instead.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] After their work was translated into Arabic in the 9th century, Al-Khwārizmī's *Book of the Description of the Earth* corrected Marinus' and Ptolemy's errors regarding the length of the Mediterranean Sea, causing medieval Arabic cartography to use a prime meridian around 10° east of Ptolemy's line.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] Mathematical cartography resumed in Europe following Maximus Planudes' recovery of Ptolemy's text a little before 1300; the text was translated into Latin at Florence by Jacopo d'Angelo around 1407.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] In 1884, the United States hosted the International Meridian Conference, attended by representatives from twenty-five nations.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] Twenty-two of them agreed to adopt the longitude of the Royal Observatory in Greenwich, England as the zero-reference line.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] The Dominican Republic voted against the motion, while France and Brazil abstained.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] France adopted Greenwich Mean Time in place of local determinations by the Paris Observatory in 1911.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] The *latitude* φ of a point on Earth's surface is defined in one of three ways, depending on the type of coordinate system.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] In each case, the latitude is the angle formed by the plane of the equator and a line formed by the point on the surface and a second point on equatorial plane.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] The path that joins all points of the same latitude traces a circle on the surface of Earth, as viewed from above the north or south pole, called parallels, as they are parallel to the equator and to each other.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] The north pole is 90° N; the south pole is 90° S.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] The 0° parallel of latitude is defined to be the equator, the fundamental plane of a geographic coordinate system.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] The equator divides the globe into Northern and Southern Hemispheres.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] The *longitude* λ of a point on Earth's surface is the angle east or west of a reference meridian to another meridian that passes through that point.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] All meridians are halves of great ellipses, which converge at the North and South Poles.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] The meridian of the British Royal Observatory in Greenwich, in southeast London, England, is the international prime meridian, although some organizations—such as the French Institut national de l'information géographique et forestière—continue to use other meridians for internal purposes.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] The antipodal meridian of Greenwich is both 180°W and 180°E.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] This is not to be conflated with the International Date Line, which partly overlaps with the 180° meridian but diverges from it in several places for political and convenience reasons, including between far eastern Russia and the far western Aleutian Islands.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] The combination of these two components specifies the position of any location on the surface of Earth, without consideration of altitude or depth.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] The visual grid on a map formed by lines of latitude and longitude is known as a *graticule*.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] The origin/zero point of this system is located in the Gulf of Guinea about 625 km (390 mi) south of Tema, Ghana, a location often facetiously called Null Island.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] In order to use the theoretical definitions of latitude, longitude, and height to precisely measure actual locations on the physical earth, a *geodetic datum* must be used.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] A *horizonal datum* is used to precisely measure latitude and longitude, while a *vertical datum* is used to measure elevation or altitude.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] Both types of datum bind a mathematical model of the shape of the earth (usually a reference ellipsoid for a horizontal datum, and a more precise geoid for a vertical datum) to the earth.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] Traditionally, this binding was created by a network of control points, surveyed locations at which monuments are installed, and were only accurate for a region of the surface of the Earth.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] Newer datums are based on a global network for satellite measurements (GNSS, VLBI, SLR and DORIS).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] This combination of a mathematical model and physical binding ensures that users of the same datum obtain identical coordinates for a given physical point.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] However, different datums typically produce different coordinates for the same location (sometimes deviating several hundred meters) not due to actual movement, but because the reference system itself is shifted.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] Because any spatial reference system or map projection is ultimately calculated from latitude and longitude, it is crucial that they clearly state the datum on which they are based.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] For example, a UTM coordinate based on a WGS84 realisation will be different than a UTM coordinate based on NAD27 for the same location.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] Transforming coordinates from one datum to another requires a datum transformation method such as a Helmert transformation, although in certain situations a simple translation may be sufficient.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] Datums may be global, meaning that they represent the whole Earth, or they may be regional, meaning that they represent an ellipsoid best-fit to only a portion of the Earth.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] Datums with a regional fit of the ellipsoid that are chosen by a national cartographical organization include the North American Datums, the European ED50, and the British OSGB36.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] Given a location, the datum provides the latitude $\phi$ and longitude $\lambda$ .
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] In the United Kingdom there are three common latitude, longitude, and height systems in use.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] WGS 84 differs at Greenwich from the one used on published maps OSGB36 by approximately 112 m.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] Points on the Earth's surface move relative to each other due to continental plate motion, subsidence, and diurnal Earth tidal movement caused by the Moon and the Sun.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] This daily movement can be as much as a meter.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] Continental movement can be up to 10 cm a year, or 10 m in a century.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] A weather system high-pressure area can cause a sinking of 5 mm.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] Scandinavia is rising by 1 cm a year as a result of the melting of the ice sheets of the last ice age, but neighboring Scotland is rising by only 0.2 cm.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] These changes are insignificant if a regional datum is used, but are statistically significant if a global datum is used.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] On the GRS 80 or WGS 84 spheroid at sea level at the Equator, one latitudinal second measures 30.715 m, one latitudinal minute is 1843 m and one latitudinal degree is 110.6 km.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] The circles of longitude, meridians, meet at the geographical poles, with the west–east width of a second naturally decreasing as latitude increases.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] On the Equator at sea level, one longitudinal second measures 30.92 m, a longitudinal minute is 1855 m and a longitudinal degree is 111.3 km.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] The returned measure of meters per degree latitude varies continuously with latitude.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] The formulae both return units of meters per degree.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] ( $\textstyle {\beta }\,\!$ is known as the reduced (or parametric) latitude).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] Aside from rounding, this is the exact distance along a parallel of latitude; getting the distance along the shortest route will be more work, but those two distances are always within 0.6 m of each other if the two points are one degree of longitude apart.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] Like any series of multiple-digit numbers, latitude-longitude pairs can be challenging to communicate and remember.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/geographic-coordinate-system] These are not distinct coordinate systems, only alternative methods for expressing latitude and longitude measurements.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Previously a part of Virginia, Kentucky was admitted into the Union as the fifteenth state on June 1, 1792.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] It is known as the "Bluegrass State" in reference to Kentucky bluegrass, a species of grass introduced by European settlers, which has long supported the state's thoroughbred horse industry.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The fertile soil in the central and western parts of the state led to the development of large tobacco plantations similar to those in Virginia and North Carolina, which utilized slave labor prior to the passage of the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Kentucky ranks fifth nationally in goat farming, eighth in beef cattle production, and fourteenth in corn production.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] While Kentucky has been a long-standing center for the tobacco industry, its economy has diversified into non-agricultural sectors including auto manufacturing, energy production, and medicine.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Kentucky ranks fourth among US states in the number of automobiles and trucks assembled.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] It is one of several states considered part of the Upland South.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The state is home to the world's longest known cave system in Mammoth Cave National Park, the greatest length of navigable waterways and streams in the contiguous United States, and the nation's two largest artificial lakes east of the Mississippi River.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Cultural aspects of Kentucky include horse racing, bourbon, moonshine, coal mining, My Old Kentucky Home State Park, automobile manufacturing, tobacco, Southern cuisine, barbecue, bluegrass music, college basketball, Louisville Slugger baseball bats, and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Prior to 1769, Botetourt County and successor counties in the Colony of Virginia, whose geographical extent was south of the Ohio and Allegheny Rivers beyond the Appalachian Mountains, became known to European Americans as *Kentucky (or Kentucke) country*.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] It was named for the Kentucky River, a tributary of the Ohio.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The precise etymology of the name is uncertain.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] One theory sees the word based on an Iroquoian name meaning "(on) the meadow" or "(on) the prairie" (cf.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Mohawk **kenhtà:ke**; Seneca **gëdá'geh** ([kɛ̃taʔkɛh]), both meaning "at the field").
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Another theory suggests a derivation from the term **Kenta Aki**, which could have come from an Algonquian language, in particular from Shawnee.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Folk etymology translates this as "Land of Our Fathers".
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The closest approximation in another Algonquian language, Ojibwe, translates as "Land of Our In-Laws", thus making a fairer English translation "The Land of Those Who Became Our Fathers".
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] In any case, the word **aki** means "land" in most Algonquian languages.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The first archaeological evidence of human occupation of Kentucky is approximately 9500 BCE, and it was Clovis culture, primitive hunter-gatherers with stone tools.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Around 1800 BCE, a gradual transition began from a hunter-gatherer economy to agriculturalism.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Around 900 CE, a Mississippian culture took root in western and central Kentucky and a Fort Ancient culture appeared in eastern Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] While the two had many similarities, the distinctive ceremonial earthwork mounds constructed in the former's centers were not part of the culture of the latter.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] In about the 10th century, the Kentucky native people's variety of corn became highly productive, supplanting the Eastern Agricultural Complex and replacing it with maize-based agriculture in the Mississippian era.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] As of the 16th century, what became Kentucky was home to tribes from diverse linguistic groups.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The Kispoko, an Algonquian-speaking tribe, controlled much of the interior of the state.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The Chickasaw had territory up to the confluence of Mississippi and Ohio rivers.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] During a period known as the Beaver Wars (1640–1680), another Algonquian tribe called the Maumee, or Mascouten was chased out of southern Michigan.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The vast majority of them moved to Kentucky, pushing the Kispoko east and war broke out with the Tutelo of North Carolina and Virginia that pushed them further north and east.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The Maumee were closely related to the Miami from Indiana.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Later, the Kispoko merged with the Shawnee, who migrated from the east and the Ohio River valley.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] A persistent myth, perpetuated in many popular and scholarly works, alleges that Native Americans never lived permanently in Kentucky, but rather used it only as a "hunting ground".
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] These sites and artifacts were sometimes explained as being the remnants of a "lost" white race, or some variously identified ethnic group predating and distinct from the Native Americans.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] More recent scholarship identifies the mound builders as the Mississippian and Fort Ancient peoples, which were distinct from the indigenous cultures encountered by settlers, although sharing the same origin in Paleoindian groups that inhabited the area for at least 12,000 years.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Beginning in the seventeenth century, before indigenous groups in Kentucky made direct contact with Europeans, articles of European origin such as glass beads entered the region via trade routes, and the appearance of mass graves suggests that European diseases were also introduced.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] By the eighteenth century, epidemics of disease had destabilized and changed the indigenous groups that inhabited Kentucky, causing some to reassemble into multi-tribal towns, and others to disperse further from the sphere of European influence.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Around the end of the French and Indian War, as European settlers began to claim parts of the Bluegrass State, Native Americans abandoned their larger, more permanent villages south of the Ohio River and continued to maintain only small or transient settlements.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] This upheaval allowed the settlers to state that Kentucky was a hunting ground contested by multiple tribes but not permanently inhabited, when in reality it had only recently been abandoned due to social and political turmoil.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] European explorers arrived in Kentucky possibly as early as 1671.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] While French explorers surely spied Kentucky during expeditions on the Mississippi, there is no evidence French or Spanish explorers set foot in the lands south of the Ohio, notwithstanding speculations about Hernando de Soto and Robert de la Salle.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The terrain in those days was not surveyed, so there is some uncertainty whether and to what extent the early English explorers out of Virginia set foot on the land.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Confounding the issue is that the region south of the Ohio/Allegheny later known as *Kentucky country* was larger than the state of Kentucky today, encompassing most of today's West Virginia and (vaguely) part of southwestern Pennsylvania.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Notable expeditions were Batts and Fallam 1671, Needham and Arthur 1673.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Thomas Walker and surveyor Christopher Gist surveyed the area now known as Kentucky in 1750 and 1751.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] As more settlers entered the area, warfare broke out with the Native Americans over their traditional hunting grounds.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] June 16, 1774, James Harrod founded Harrod's Town (modern Harrodsburg).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The settlement was abandoned during the conflict period of Dunmore's War, and resettled in March 1775, becoming the first permanent European settlement in Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] It was followed within months by Boone's Station, Logan's Fort and Lexington before Kentucky was organized.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] This period was the time of Daniel Boone's legendary expeditions starting in 1767 through the Cumberland Gap and down the Kentucky River to reach the bluegrass heartland of Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] While the Cherokee did not settle in Kentucky, they hunted there.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] They relinquished their hunting rights there in an extra-legal private contract with speculator Richard Henderson called *Treaty of Sycamore Shoals* in 1775.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Harrod's Town (Oldtown as it was known at the time) was named the county seat.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] A 1790 U.S. government report states that 1,500 Kentucky settlers had been killed by Native Americans since the end of the Revolutionary War.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The county was subdivided into Jefferson, Lincoln and Fayette Counties in 1780, but continued to be administered as the District of Kentucky even as new counties were split off.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] On several occasions the region's residents petitioned the General Assembly and the Confederation Congress for separation from Virginia and statehood.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Ten constitutional conventions were held in Danville between 1784 and 1792.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] One petition, which had Virginia's assent, came before the Confederation Congress in early July 1788.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Unfortunately, its consideration came up a day after word of New Hampshire's all-important ninth ratification of the proposed Constitution, thus establishing it as the new framework of governance for the United States.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] In light of this development, Congress thought that it would be "unadvisable" to admit Kentucky into the Union, as it could do so "under the Articles of Confederation" only, but not "under the Constitution", and so declined to take action.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] On December 18, 1789, Virginia again gave its consent to Kentucky statehood.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The United States Congress gave its approval on February 4, 1791.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] (This occurred two weeks before Congress approved Vermont's petition for statehood.) Kentucky officially became the fifteenth state in the Union on June 1, 1792.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Isaac Shelby, a military veteran from Virginia, was elected its first Governor.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The central Bluegrass region and the western portion of the state were the areas with the most slave owners.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Planters cultivated tobacco and hemp on plantations with the use of slave labor, and were noted for their quality livestock.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] During the 19th century, Kentucky slaveholders began to sell unneeded slaves to the Deep South, with Louisville becoming a major slave market and departure port for slaves being transported down the Ohio River.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Kentucky was a heavily divided border slave state during the American Civil War, with the population split between Unionists and those sympathetic to the seceded Confederate States.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Though the state had dueling Union and Confederate state governments, Kentucky remained part of the Union throughout the war – although it declared that it was officially "neutral", a position that Abraham Lincoln worked hard to honor.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] After a failed attempt by Confederate General Leonidas Polk to take the state for the Confederacy, the legislature petitioned the Union Army for assistance.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] In 1861, representatives from 68 of 110 counties, representing about half the state's territory, met at Russellville calling themselves the "Convention of the People of Kentucky" and passed an Ordinance of Secession on November 20.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] They established a Confederate government of Kentucky with its capital in Bowling Green, and Kentucky was officially admitted into the Confederacy on December 10, 1861, as the 13th Confederate state with full recognition in Richmond.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The Confederate shadow government was never popularly elected statewide.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Although Confederate forces briefly controlled Frankfort, the state capital, they were expelled by Union forces before a Confederate government could be installed.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] With the expulsion of Confederate forces after the Battle of Perryville, this government operated in exile.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Though it existed throughout the war, the Confederate government only had authority in areas of the state under its direct control, and had very little effect on the events in the commonwealth or in the war once they were driven out of the state.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Some 21st-century Kentuckians observe Confederate Memorial Day on Confederate leader Jefferson Davis' birthday, June 3, and participate in Confederate battle re-enactments.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Both Davis and U.S. president Abraham Lincoln were born in Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Breckinridge, the 14th and youngest-ever Vice President, and the Southern Democratic Party candidate for the Presidency in the 1860 election, was born near Lexington, Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Senate after he accepted a commission in the Confederate Army.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] On January 30, 1900, Governor William Goebel, flanked by two bodyguards, was mortally wounded by an assassin while walking to the State Capitol in downtown Frankfort.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Goebel was contesting the Kentucky gubernatorial election of 1899, which William S.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Taylor was initially believed to have won.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Beckham, Goebel's running mate, and Taylor fought over who was the legal governor until the Supreme Court of the United States ruled in May in favor of Beckham.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] After fleeing to Indiana, Taylor was indicted as a co-conspirator in Goebel's assassination.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Goebel is the only governor of a U.S. state to have been assassinated while in office.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The Black Patch Tobacco Wars, a vigilante action, occurred in Western Kentucky in the early 20th century.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] As a result of the tobacco industry monopoly, tobacco farmers in the area were forced to sell their crops at prices that were too low.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Many local farmers and activists united in a refusal to sell their crops to the major tobacco companies.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] An Association meeting occurred in downtown Guthrie, where a vigilante wing of "Night Riders", formed.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The riders terrorized farmers who sold their tobacco at the low prices demanded by the tobacco corporations.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] They burned several tobacco warehouses throughout the area, stretching as far west as Hopkinsville to Princeton.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] In the later period of their operation, they were known to physically assault farmers who broke the boycott.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Willson declared martial law and deployed the Kentucky National Guard to end the wars.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Kentucky is situated in the Upland South.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] A significant portion of eastern Kentucky is part of Appalachia.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Kentucky borders seven states, from the Midwest and the Southeast.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] West Virginia lies to the northeast, Virginia to the east, Tennessee to the south, Missouri to the west, Illinois to the northwest, and Indiana and Ohio to the north.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Only Missouri and Tennessee, both of which border eight states, touch more.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Kentucky's northern border is formed by the north shore of the Ohio River and its western border by the Mississippi River; however, the official border is based on the courses of the rivers as they existed when Kentucky became a state in 1792.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] For instance, northbound travelers on U.S.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] 41 from Henderson, after crossing the Ohio River, will be in Kentucky for about two miles (3 km).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Ellis Park, a thoroughbred racetrack, is located in this small piece of Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Waterworks Road is part of the only land border between Indiana and Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Kentucky has a non-contiguous part known as Kentucky Bend, at the far west corner of the state.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] It exists as an exclave surrounded completely by Missouri and Tennessee, and is included in the boundaries of Fulton County.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Road access to this small part of Kentucky on the Mississippi River (populated by 18 people as of 2010) requires traveling through Tennessee.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The epicenter of the 1811–12 New Madrid earthquakes was near this area, causing the Mississippi River to flow backwards in some places.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Though the series of quakes changed the area geologically and affected the small number of inhabitants of the area at the time, the Kentucky Bend is the result of a surveying error, not the New Madrid earthquake.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The Bluegrass region is commonly divided into two regions, the Inner Bluegrass encircling 90 miles (140 km) around Lexington, and the Outer Bluegrass that contains most of the northern portion of the state, above the Knobs.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Much of the outer Bluegrass is in the Eden Shale Hills sub-region, made up of short, steep, and very narrow hills.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The alluvial plain of the Ohio River is another geological region, as is the area south and east of Pine Mountain, part of the Ridge and Valley Belt of Appalachia.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Most of Kentucky has a humid subtropical climate (Köppen: *Cfa*), with small Appalachian highland areas of the southeast of the state having an oceanic climate (*Cfb*).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Temperatures in Kentucky usually range from daytime summer highs of 87 °F (31 °C) to the winter low of 23 °F (−5 °C).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The average precipitation is 46 inches (1,200 mm) a year.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Kentucky has four distinct seasons, with substantial variations in the severity of summer and winter.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The state's highest recorded temperature was 114 °F (46 °C) in Greensburg on July 28, 1930, while its lowest recorded temperature was −37 °F (−38 °C) in Shelbyville on January 19, 1994.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The state seldom experiences the extreme cold of far northern states or the high heat of the states in the Deep South; temperatures rarely drop below zero degrees Fahrenheit or rise above 100 degrees.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Rain and snowfall averages about 45 inches per year.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The climate varies markedly within the state.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The northern parts tend to be about five degrees cooler than those in the western parts of the state.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Somerset in the south-central part receives ten more inches of rain per year than Covington to the north.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Average temperatures for the entire state range from the low 30s in January to the high 80s in mid-July.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The annual average temperature varies from 55 to 60 °F (13 to 16 °C): of 55 °F (13 °C) in the far north as an average annual temperature and of 60 °F (16 °C) in the extreme southwest.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] In general, Kentucky has relatively hot, humid, rainy summers, and moderately cold and rainy winters.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Mean maximum temperatures in July vary from 83 to 90 °F (28 to 32 °C); the mean minimum July temperatures are 61 to 69 °F (16 to 21 °C).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] In January the mean maximum temperatures range from 36 to 44 °F (2 to 7 °C); the mean minimum temperatures range from 19 to 26 °F (−7 to −3 °C).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Temperature means vary with northern and far-eastern mountain regions averaging five degrees cooler year-round, compared to the relatively warmer areas of the southern and western regions of the state.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Precipitation varies north to south with the north averaging of 38 to 40 inches (970 to 1,020 mm), and the south averaging of 50 inches (1,300 mm).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Days per year below the freezing point vary from about sixty days in the southwest to more than a hundred days in the far-north and far-east.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Kentucky has the second-most navigable miles of water among U.S. states, second to Alaska.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Kentucky is the only state to have a continuous border of rivers running along three of its sides – the Mississippi River to the west, the Ohio River to the north, and the Big Sandy River and Tug Fork to the east.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Its major internal rivers include the Kentucky River, Tennessee River, Cumberland River, Green River, and Licking River.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Though it has only three major natural lakes, Kentucky is home to many artificial lakes.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] It has the largest artificial lakes east of the Mississippi in both water volume (Lake Cumberland) and surface area (Kentucky Lake).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Kentucky Lake's 2,064 miles (3,322 km) of shoreline, 160,300 acres (64,900 hectares) of water surface, and 4,008,000 acre-feet (4.9 billion cubic meters) of flood storage are the most of any lake in the Tennessee Valley Authority system.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Kentucky's 90,000 miles (140,000 km) of streams provides one of the most expansive and complex stream systems in the nation.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Kentucky hosts multiple habitats with a high number of endemic species, including some of the most extensive cave systems in the world.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] 102 known species are endemic to the state.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The Bluegrass region, which is believed to have once been a lush open woodland environment similar to oak savanna with abundant thickets of river cane, a species of bamboo, was once described by E.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Lucy Braun as having the most "anomalous" plant life of the whole Eastern United States.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Kentucky's natural environment has suffered greatly from destructive human activities that began after European colonization, particularly the conversion of natural habitat to farmland and coal mining.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Kentucky has an expansive park system, which includes one national park, two National Recreation Areas, two National Historic Parks, two national forests, two National Wildlife Refuges, 45 state parks, 37,896 acres (153 km2) of state forest, and 82 wildlife management areas.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Kentucky has been part of two of the most successful wildlife reintroduction projects in United States history.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] In the winter of 1997, the Kentucky Department of Fish and Wildlife Resources began to re-stock elk in the state's eastern counties, which had been extirpated from the area for over 150 years.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] As of 2009, the herd had reached the project goal of 10,000 animals, making it the largest herd east of the Mississippi River.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The state stocked wild turkeys in the 1950s, after reportedly having fewer than 900.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Once nearly extinct, wild turkeys thrive throughout Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Hunters reported a record 29,006 birds taken during the 23-day season in spring 2009.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] In 1991 the Land Between the Lakes partnered with the U.S.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Fish and Wildlife Service for the Red Wolf Recovery Program, a captive breeding program.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Kentucky is subdivided into 120 counties, the largest being Pike County at 787.6 square miles (2,040 km2), and the most populous being Jefferson County (which coincides with the Louisville Metro governmental area) with 772,144 residents as of 2023.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] County government, under the Kentucky Constitution of 1891, is vested in the County Judge/Executive, (formerly called the County Judge) who serves as the executive head of the county, and a legislature called a Fiscal Court.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Despite the unusual name, the Fiscal Court no longer has judicial functions.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Kentucky's two most populous counties, Jefferson and Fayette, have their governments consolidated with the governments of their largest cities.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Although the counties still exist as subdivisions of the state, in reference the names Louisville and Lexington are used to refer to the entire area coextensive with the former cities and counties.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The Metro Louisville government area has a 2018 population of 1,298,990.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Under United States Census Bureau methodology, the population of Louisville was 623,867.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The latter figure is the population of the so-called "balance" – the parts of Jefferson County that were either unincorporated or within the City of Louisville before the formation of the merged government in 2003.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] In 2018 the Louisville Combined Statistical Area (CSA) had a population of 1,569,112; including 1,209,191 in Kentucky, which means more than 25% of the state's population now lives in the Louisville CSA.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Since 2000, over one-third of the state's population growth has occurred in the Louisville CSA.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] In addition, the top 28 wealthiest places in Kentucky are in Jefferson County and seven of the 15 wealthiest counties in the state are located in the Louisville CSA.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The state's second-largest city is Lexington with a 2018 census population of 323,780, its metro had a population of 516,697, and its CSA, which includes the Frankfort and Richmond statistical areas, having a population of 746,310.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The Northern Kentucky area, which comprises the seven Kentucky counties in the Cincinnati/Northern Kentucky metropolitan area, had a population of 447,457 in 2018.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The metropolitan areas of Louisville, Lexington, and Northern Kentucky have a combined population of 2,402,958 as of 2018, which is 54% of the state's total population on only about 19% of the state's land.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] This area is often referred to as the Golden triangle as it contains a majority of the state's wealth, population, population growth, and economic growth, it is where most of the state's largest cities by population are located.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] It is referred to as the Golden triangle as the metro areas of Lexington, Louisville, and Northern Kentucky/Cincinnati outline a triangle shape.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Interstates I-71, I-75, and I-64 form the triangle shape.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Additionally, all counties in Kentucky that are part of an MSA or CSA have a total population of 2,970,694, which is 67% of the state's population.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] As of 2017 Bowling Green had a population of 67,067, making it the third most populous city in the state.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The Bowling Green metropolitan area had an estimated population of 174,835; and the combined statistical area it shares with Glasgow has an estimated population of 228,743.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The two other fast-growing urban areas in Kentucky are the Bowling Green area and the "Tri-Cities Region" of southeastern Kentucky, comprising Somerset, London and Corbin.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Although only one town in the "Tri-Cities" (Somerset) currently has more than 12,000 people, the area has been experiencing heightened population and job growth since the 1990s.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Growth has been especially rapid in Laurel County, which outgrew areas such as Scott and Jessamine counties around Lexington or Shelby and Nelson Counties around Louisville.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] London significantly grew in population in the 2000s, from 5,692 in 2000 to 7,993 in 2010.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] London landed a Wal-Mart distribution center in 1997, bringing thousands of jobs to the community.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] In northeast Kentucky, the greater Ashland area is an important transportation, manufacturing, and medical center.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Iron and petroleum production, as well as the transport of coal by rail and barge, have been historical pillars of the region's economy.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Due to a decline in the area's industrial base, Ashland has seen a sizable reduction in its population since 1990; however, the population of the area has since stabilized with the medical service industry taking a greater role in the local economy.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The Ashland area, including the counties of Boyd and Greenup, is part of the Huntington-Ashland, WV-KY-OH, Metropolitan Statistical Area (MSA).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] As of the 2000 census, the MSA had a population of 288,649.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] More than 21,000 of those people (as of 2010) reside within the city limits of Ashland.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The largest county in Kentucky by area is Pike, which contains Pikeville and suburb Coal Run Village.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Pike County contains slightly more than 68,000 people.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Only three U.S. states have capitals with smaller populations than Kentucky's Frankfort (pop.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The United States Census Bureau determined that the population of Kentucky was 4,505,836 in 2020, increasing since the 2010 United States census.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] As of July 1, 2016, Kentucky had an estimated population of 4,436,974, which is an increase of 12,363 from the prior year and an increase of 97,607, or 2.2%, since the year 2010.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] This includes a natural increase since the last census of 73,541 people (that is 346,968 births minus 273,427 deaths) and an increase due to net migration of 26,135 people into the state.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Immigration from outside the United States resulted in a net increase of 40,051 people, and migration within the country produced a net decrease of 13,916 people.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] As of 2015, Kentucky's population included about 149,016 foreign-born persons (3.4%).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] In 2016 the population density of the state was 110 people per square mile (42 people/km2).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Mexico, India, Cuba, China, and Guatemala are the top five countries of origin for Kentucky's immigrants.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Kentucky's population has grown every decade since records began, though during most decades of the 20th century there was net out-migration from the state.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Since 1900, rural Kentucky counties have suffered a net loss of more than a million people to migration, while urban areas have experienced a slight net gain.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Kentucky's center of population is in Washington County, in the city of Willisburg.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] According to HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 3,984 homeless people in Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Life expectancy in Kentucky was 72.5 years in 2021.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Census Bureau official statistics, the state's largest ancestry in 2013 was American, totalling 20.2%.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] In 1980, before the status of ethnic American was an available option on the official census, the largest claimed ancestries in the commonwealth were English (49.6%), Irish (26.3%), and German (24.2%).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] In the urban counties of Jefferson, Oldham, Fayette, Boone, Kenton, and Campbell, German is the largest reported ancestry.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Americans of Scotch-Irish and English ancestry are present throughout the entire state.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Many residents claim Irish ancestry on account of Scotch-Irish (Ulster Scots) descent.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] In the 1980s, the only counties in the United States where over half of the population cited "English" as their only ancestry group were in eastern Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] In the 2000 census, some 20,000 people (0.49%) in the state self-identified as Native American.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The state has no federally recognized tribes or state-recognized tribes.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] African Americans, who before the Civil War were mostly slaves, made up 25% of Kentucky's population around that time; they were held and worked primarily in the central Bluegrass region, an area of hemp and tobacco cultivation as well as the raising of blooded livestock.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The number of African Americans living in Kentucky declined during the 20th century amid the Great Migration.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] In the 2020 Census, 362,417 Kentucky residents were identified as African American (8% of the total 4,505,836).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The state's African-American population is highly urbanized, with 44.2% living in Jefferson County and 52% living in the broader Louisville metropolitan area.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Other areas with high concentrations include Christian and Fulton counties and the cities of Paducah and Lexington.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] African Americans in the seven counties of Jefferson (168,910), Fayette (48,076), Christian (15,527), Warren (12,933), Hardin (12,825), Kenton (8,195), and McCracken (7,598) make up more than 75% of all African Americans in the state.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The Hispanic and Asian populations in Kentucky are small but have grown significantly since the late 20th century.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Most of Kentucky's Hispanic residents are of Mexican ancestry, while most of Kentucky's Asian residents are of Chinese and Indian heritage.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] There is also a Vietnamese community in Lexington and Louisville, and Vietnamese, Cambodian, and Lao populations in Bowling Green.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] In 2000, 96% of all residents of the state five years old and older spoke only English at home, a small decrease from 98% in 1990.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Speech patterns in the state generally reflect the first settlers' Virginia backgrounds.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] South Midland features are best preserved in the mountains, with Southern in most other areas of Kentucky, but some common to Midland and Southern are widespread.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] After a vowel, the /r/ may be weak or missing.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] For instance, *Coop* has the vowel of *put*, but the root rhymes with *boot*.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] In southern Kentucky, earthworms are called *redworms*, a burlap bag is known as a *tow sack* or the *Southern grass sack*, and green beans are called *snap beans*.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] In Kentucky English, a young man may *carry*, not escort, his girlfriend to a party.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Spanish is the second-most-spoken language in Kentucky, after English.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Being a Southern state in the Bible Belt, Kentucky is predominantly Christian and is home to several seminaries.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Southern Baptist Theological Seminary in Louisville is the principal seminary for the Southern Baptist Convention.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Louisville is the home of the Louisville Presbyterian Theological Seminary, an institution of the Presbyterian Church (USA).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Lexington has one seminary, Lexington Theological Seminary (affiliated with the Disciples of Christ).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The Baptist Seminary of Kentucky is located on the campus of Georgetown College in Georgetown.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Asbury Theological Seminary, a multi-denominational seminary in the Methodist tradition, is located in nearby Wilmore.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Louisville is home to the Cathedral of the Assumption, the third-oldest Catholic cathedral in continuous use in the United States.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The city holds the headquarters of the Presbyterian Church (USA) and their printing press.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] Reflecting late 19th, 20th and 21st-century immigration from different countries, Louisville also has Jewish, Muslim, and Hindu communities.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] In 1996 the Center for Interfaith Relations established the Festival of Faiths, the first and oldest annual interfaith festival to be held in the United States.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p01] The Christian creationist apologetics group, Answers in Genesis, along with its Creation Museum, is headquartered in Petersburg, Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In 2025, Kentucky's total gross state product was $306.8 billion.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In 2025, Kentucky's per capita personal income was $60,673.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In 2025, small businesses made up 99.3% of all businesses in the state, and employed 42.6% of the Kentucky's workforce.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] As of May 2025, the state's unemployment rate was 5%.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Early in its history, Kentucky gained recognition for its excellent farming conditions.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] It was the site of the first commercial winery in the United States (started in present-day Jessamine County in 1799) and due to the high calcium content of the soil in the Bluegrass region quickly became a major horse breeding (and later racing) area.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In 2006, Kentucky ranked 5th nationally in goat farming, 8th in beef cattle production, and 14th in corn production.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky has been a long-standing major center of the tobacco industry – both as a center of business and tobacco farming.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky's economy has expanded to in non-agricultural terms as well, especially auto manufacturing, energy fuel production, and medical facilities.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky ranked 4th among U.S. states in the number of automobiles and trucks assembled in 2003.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky has historically been a major coal producer, but the industry has been in decline since the 1980s, and the number employed dropped by more than half between 2011 and 2015.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In August 2025, General Matter, an American uranium enrichment company, signed a lease with the U.S.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Department of Energy for the former Paducah Gaseous Diffusion Plant.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Plans for the $1.5 billion updated facility include uranium enrichment technology for the production of fuel needed for the next generation of nuclear energy.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In January 2026, General Matter received a $900 million contract from the U.S.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Department of Energy for re-shoring to produce American enriched uranium.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky produces 95% of the world's supply of bourbon whiskey, and the number of barrels of bourbon being aged in Kentucky (more than 5.7 million) exceeds the state's population.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Bourbon has been a growing market – with production of Kentucky bourbon rising 170 percent between 1999 and 2015.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In 2019 the state had more than fifty distilleries for bourbon production.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky exports reached $22.1 billion in 2012, with products and services going to 199 countries.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Fort Knox, a United States Army post best known as the site of the United States Bullion Depository, which is used to house a large portion of the United States official gold reserves, is located in Kentucky between Louisville and Elizabethtown.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In May 2010, the Army Human Resource Center of Excellence, the largest office building in the state consisting of six interconnected, three-story buildings, at nearly 900,000 square feet (84,000 m2), opened at Fort Knox.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The complex consolidated facilities from Virginia, Indiana and Missouri, and employs nearly 4,300 soldiers and civilians.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The new Louisville VA Medical Center, with a 34-acre campus, is scheduled for completion in late 2026, with its first patient in 2027.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] This nearly $1 billion, million-square-foot facility on Brownsboro Road features 104 beds and advanced modern state-of-the-art medical services.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Replacing a 75-year-old facility, it will serve over 45,000 veterans in Kentucky and Southern Indiana.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Hundreds of health care workers will be employed at the center.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky contains two of the twenty U.S.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Federal Penitentiaries: USP Big Sandy (in the east in Martin County near Inez) and USP McCreary (in the south in McCreary County in the Daniel Boone National Forest).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Since 2020, major economic announcements have accelerated throughout the state.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Many major US and foreign corporations, including ExxonMobil, Apple, Envision AESC, Canadian Solar, General Matter, General Motors, Ford, GE Appliances, Kingspan Group, Toyota, Foxconn, Kroger, and Beam Suntory, have expanded their presence.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Tax is collected by the Kentucky Department of Revenue.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky has a flat 4% individual income tax rate.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky has a broadly based classified property tax system.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] All classes of property, unless exempted by the Constitution, are taxed by the state, although at widely varying rates.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Many of these classes are exempted from taxation by local government.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Of the classes that are subject to local taxation, three have special rates set by the General Assembly, one by the Kentucky Supreme Court and the remaining classes are subject to the full local rate, which includes the tax rate set by the local taxing bodies plus all voted levies.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Real property is assessed on 100% of the fair market value and property taxes are due by December 31.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Once the primary source of state and local government revenue, property taxes now account for only about 6% of the Kentucky's annual General Fund revenues.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Until January 1, 2006, Kentucky imposed a tax on intangible personal property held by a taxpayer on January 1 of each year.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The Kentucky intangible tax was repealed under House Bill 272.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Intangible property consisted of any property or investment that represents evidence of value or the right to value.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Some types of intangible property included: bonds, notes, retail repurchase agreements, accounts receivable, trusts, enforceable contracts sale of real estate (land contracts), money in hand, money in safe deposit boxes, annuities, interests in estates, loans to stockholders, and commercial paper.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In 2023, Kentucky launched a regulated local and online sports betting industry.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Taxing sportsbooks at 9.75% (in person) and 14.25% (online), the first two months of action saw the state collect $7.94 million.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Tourism has become an increasingly important part of the Kentucky economy.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In 2019 tourism grew to $7.6 billion in economic impact.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The National Corvette Museum in Bowling Green caters to sports car enthusiasts.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Waterfront Botanical Gardens is an urban garden just outside Downtown Louisville.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The Big Four Bridge, visited by 1.5 million visitors a year, is a pedestrian/bicycle bridge that crosses over the Ohio River from Louisville Waterfront Park to Jeffersonville, Indiana.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The state also has religious destinations such as the Creation Museum and Ark Encounter of Answers in Genesis.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In December 2002, the Kentucky governor Paul E.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Patton unveiled the state slogan "It's that friendly", in the hope of drawing more people into the state based on the idea of southern hospitality.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Though it was meant to embrace southern values, many Kentuckians rejected the slogan as cheesy and generic.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] It was seen that the slogan did not encourage tourism as much as initially hoped for.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In 2004, then Governor Ernie Fletcher launched a comprehensive branding campaign with the hope of making the state's $12–14 million advertising budget more effective.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The resulting "Unbridled Spirit" brand was the result of a $500,000 contract with New West, a Kentucky-based public relations advertising and marketing firm, to develop a viable brand and tag line.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The Fletcher administration aggressively marketed the brand in both the public and private sectors.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Since that time, the "Welcome to Kentucky" signs at border areas have an "Unbridled Spirit" symbol on them.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Horse racing has long been associated with Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Churchill Downs, the home of the Derby, is a large venue with a capacity exceeding 165,000.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The track hosts multiple events throughout the year and is a significant draw to the city of Louisville.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Keeneland Race Course, in Lexington, hosts two major meets, the Spring and Fall running.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Beyond hosting races Keeneland also hosts a significant horse auction drawing buyers from around the world.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In 2019 $360 million was spent on the September Yearling sale.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The Kentucky Horse Park in Georgetown hosts multiple events throughout the year, including international equestrian competitions and also offers horseback riding from April to October.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky maintains eight public four-year universities.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] There are two general tiers: major research institutions (the University of Kentucky and the University of Louisville) and regional universities, which encompass the remaining six schools.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The regional schools have specific target counties that many of their programs are targeted towards (such as Forestry at Eastern Kentucky University or Cave Management at Western Kentucky University), however, most of their curriculum varies little from any other public university.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] UK is the flagship and land grant of the system and has agriculture extension services in every county.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The two research schools split duties related to the medical field, UK handles all medical outreach programs in the eastern half of the state while UofL does all medical outreach in the state's western half.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The state's sixteen public two-year colleges have been governed by the Kentucky Community and Technical College System since the passage of the Postsecondary Education Improvement Act of 1997, commonly referred to as House Bill 1.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Before the passage of House Bill 1, most of these colleges were under the control of the University of Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Transylvania University, a liberal arts university located in Lexington, was founded in 1780 as the oldest university west of the Allegheny Mountains.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Berea College, located at the extreme southern edge of the Bluegrass below the Cumberland Plateau, was the first coeducational college in the South to admit both Black and white students, doing so from its very establishment in 1855.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] A state law in 1904 ended integration, and the law was upheld by the United States Supreme Court in the case of *Berea College v.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky* in 1908.The state law was repealed in 1950 and Berea resumed integration.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] There are 173 school districts and 1,233 public schools in Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] For the 2010 to 2011 school year, there were approximately 647,827 students enrolled in public school.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky has been the site of much educational reform over the past two decades.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In 1989 the Kentucky Supreme Court ruled the state's education system was unconstitutional.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The response of the General Assembly was passage of the Kentucky Education Reform Act (KERA) the following year.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Years later, Kentucky has shown progress, but most agree that further reform is needed.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The West Virginia teachers' strike in 2018 inspired teachers in other states, including Kentucky, to take similar action.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The parkways were originally toll roads, but on November 22, 2006, Governor Ernie Fletcher ended the toll charges on the William H.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Natcher Parkway and the Audubon Parkway, the last two parkways in Kentucky to charge tolls for access.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The related toll booths have been demolished.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In June 2007, a law went into effect raising the speed limit on rural portions of Kentucky Interstates and parkways from 65 to 70 miles per hour (105 to 113 km/h).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The multi-billion-dollar Brent Spence Bridge Corridor Project across the Ohio River, will construct a new double-deck companion bridge to carry interstate highway through-traffic, while the existing Brent Spence Bridge will be reconfigured for local traffic only, between Cincinnati and Covington.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Approximately eight miles of improved roadways spanning Kentucky and Ohio will be constructed.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The total project cost is estimated at $3.6 billion, and a federal grant of $1.6 billion was awarded in late 2022 to the project, with the remaining cost evenly split between Ohio and Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Major construction is expected to begin in 2026.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Also across the Ohio River, the I-69 Ohio River Crossing has been under development since 2022.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Connecting Evansville, Indiana and Henderson, Kentucky, the bridge will cost around $1.5 billion.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Construction is slated to start in 2027, with a hopeful completion date around 2031.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Road tunnels include the interstate Cumberland Gap Tunnel and the rural Nada Tunnel.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Amtrak, the national passenger rail system, provides service to Ashland, South Portsmouth, Maysville and Fulton.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The *Cardinal* (trains 50 and 51) is the line that offers Amtrak service to Ashland, South Shore, Maysville and South Portsmouth.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The *City of New Orleans* (trains 58 and 59) serve Fulton.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The Northern Kentucky area is served by the *Cardinal* at Cincinnati Union Terminal.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The terminal is just across the Ohio River in Cincinnati.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Norfolk Southern Railway passes through the Central and Southern parts of the commonwealth, via its Cincinnati, New Orleans, and Texas Pacific (CNO&TP) subsidiary.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The line originates in Cincinnati and terminates 338 miles south in Chattanooga, Tennessee.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] As of 2004, there were approximately 2,640 miles (4,250 km) of railways in Kentucky, with about 65% of those being operated by CSX Transportation.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Coal was by far the most common cargo, accounting for 76% of cargo loaded and 61% of cargo delivered.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Bardstown features a tourist attraction known as *My Old Kentucky Dinner Train*.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Run along a 20-mile (30 km) stretch of rail purchased from CSX in 1987, guests are served a four-course meal as they make a two-and-a-half-hour round-trip between Bardstown and Limestone Springs.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The Kentucky Railway Museum is located in nearby New Haven.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Other areas in Kentucky are reclaiming old railways in rail trail projects.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] One such project is Louisville's Big Four Bridge.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] When the bridge's Indiana approach ramps opened in 2014, completing the pedestrian connection across the Ohio River, the Big Four Bridge rail trail became the second-longest pedestrian-only bridge in the world.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The longest pedestrian-only bridge is also found in Kentucky – the Newport Southbank Bridge, popularly known as the "Purple People Bridge", connecting Newport to Cincinnati, Ohio.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky's primary airports include Louisville International Airport (Standiford Field (SDF)) of Louisville, Cincinnati/Northern Kentucky International Airport (CVG) of Cincinnati/Covington, and Blue Grass Airport (LEX) in Lexington.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Louisville International Airport is home to UPS's Worldport, its international air-sorting hub.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Cincinnati/Northern Kentucky International Airport is the largest airport in the state, and is a focus city for passenger airline Delta Air Lines and headquarters of its Delta Private Jets.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The airport is one of DHL Aviation's three super-hubs, serving destinations throughout the Americas, Europe, Africa, and Asia, making it the 7th busiest airport in the U.S. and 36th in the world based on passenger and cargo operations.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] CVG is also a focus city for Frontier Airlines and is the largest O&D airport and base for Allegiant Air, along with home to a maintenance for American Airlines subsidiary PSA Airlines and Delta Air Lines subsidiary Endeavor Air.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] There are also a number of regional airports scattered across the state.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] On August 27, 2006, Blue Grass Airport was the site of a crash that killed 47 passengers and 2 crew members aboard a Bombardier CRJ designated Comair Flight 191, or Delta Air Lines Flight 5191, sometimes mistakenly identified by the press as Comair Flight 5191.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The lone survivor was the flight's first officer, James Polehinke, who doctors determined to be brain damaged and unable to recall the crash at all.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] As the state is bounded by two of the largest rivers in North America, water transportation has historically played a major role in Kentucky's economy.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Louisville was a major port for steamships in the nineteenth century.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Today, most barge traffic on Kentucky waterways consists of coal that is shipped from both the Eastern and Western Coalfields, about half of which is used locally to power many power plants located directly off the Ohio River, with the rest being exported to other countries, most notably Japan.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] As a state, Kentucky ranks 10th overall in port tonnage.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The only natural obstacle along the entire length of the Ohio River is the Falls of the Ohio, located just west of Downtown Louisville.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky is one of four U.S. states to officially use the term *commonwealth.* The term was used for Kentucky as it had also been used by Virginia, from which Kentucky was created.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The term has no particular significance in its meaning and was chosen to emphasize the distinction from the status of royal colonies as a place governed for the general welfare of the populace.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky was originally styled as the "State of Kentucky" in the act admitting it to the Union and its first constitution.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The "Commonwealth" term was used in citizen petitions submitted between 1786 and 1792 for the creation of the state.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] It was also used in the title of a history of the state that was published in 1834 and was used in various places within that book in references to Virginia and Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The other three states officially called "commonwealths" are Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, and Virginia; the territories of Puerto Rico and the Northern Mariana Islands are also formally commonwealths.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky is one of only five states that elect their state officials in odd-numbered years (the others being Louisiana, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Virginia).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky holds elections for these offices every four years in the years preceding Presidential election years.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Thus, Kentucky held gubernatorial elections in 2015, 2019 and 2023.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The executive branch is headed by the governor, who serves as both head of state and head of government.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The lieutenant governor may or may not have executive authority depending on whether the person is a member of the governor's cabinet.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Under the current Kentucky Constitution, the lieutenant governor assumes the duties of the governor only if the governor is incapacitated.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] (Before 1992 the lieutenant governor assumed power any time the governor was out of the state.) The governor and lieutenant governor usually run on a single ticket (also per a 1992 constitutional amendment) and are elected to four-year terms.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The current governor is Andy Beshear, and the lieutenant governor is Jacqueline Coleman.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The cabinet system was introduced in 1972 by Governor Wendell Ford to consolidate hundreds of government entities that reported directly to the governor's office.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Other elected constitutional offices include the secretary of state, attorney general, auditor of public accounts, state treasurer, and commissioner of agriculture.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The commonwealth's chief prosecutor, law enforcement officer, and law officer is the attorney general, currently Republican Russell Coleman.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The auditor of public accounts is Republican Allison Ball.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Republican Mark Metcalf is the current treasurer.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Republican Jonathan Shell is the current commissioner of agriculture.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky's legislative branch consists of a bicameral body known as the Kentucky General Assembly.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The Senate is considered the upper house.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] It has 38 members and is led by the president of the Senate, currently Robert Stivers (R).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The House of Representatives has 100 members, and is led by the speaker of the House, currently David Osborne of the Republican Party.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In 2016, Republicans won control of the House for the first time since 1922.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The party currently holds supermajorities in both chambers.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The Kentucky Court of Justice is headed by the chief justice of the Commonwealth.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The chief justice is appointed by, and is an elected member of, the Supreme Court of Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The current chief justice is Laurance VanMeter.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Unlike federal judges, who are usually appointed, justices serving on Kentucky state courts are chosen by the state's populace in non-partisan elections.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky's two U.S. senators are Mitch McConnell and Rand Paul, both Republicans.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The state is divided into six congressional districts, represented by Republicans James Comer (1st), Brett Guthrie (2nd), Thomas Massie (4th), Hal Rogers (5th) and Andy Barr (6th) and Democrat Morgan McGarvey (3rd).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In the federal judiciary, Kentucky is served by two United States district courts: the Eastern District of Kentucky, with its primary seat in Lexington, and the Western District of Kentucky, with its primary seat in Louisville.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Appeals are heard in the Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit, based in Cincinnati, Ohio.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky's body of laws, known as the Kentucky Revised Statutes (KRS), were enacted in 1942 to better organize and clarify the whole of Kentucky law.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The statutes are enforced by local police, sheriffs and deputy sheriffs, and constables and deputy constables.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Unless they have completed a police academy elsewhere, these officers are required to complete Police Officer Professional Standards (POPS) training at the Kentucky Department of Criminal Justice Training Center on the campus of Eastern Kentucky University in Richmond.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Additionally, in 1948, the Kentucky General Assembly established the Kentucky State Police, making it the 38th state to create a force whose jurisdiction extends throughout the given state.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky is one of the 32 states in the United States that sanctions the death penalty for certain murders defined as heinous.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Those convicted of capital crimes after March 31, 1998, are always executed by lethal injection; those convicted on or before this date may opt for the electric chair.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Only three people have been executed in Kentucky since the U.S.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Supreme Court re-instituted the practice in 1976.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The most notable execution in Kentucky was that of Rainey Bethea on August 14, 1936.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Bethea was publicly hanged in Owensboro for the rape and murder of Lischia Edwards.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Irregularities with the execution led to this becoming the last public execution in the United States.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky has been on the front lines of the debate over displaying the Ten Commandments on public property.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Supreme Court upheld the decision of the Sixth Circuit Court of Appeals that a display of the Ten Commandments in the Whitley City courthouse of McCreary County was unconstitutional.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Later that year, Judge Richard Fred Suhrheinrich, writing for the Sixth Circuit Court of Appeals in the case of *ACLU of Kentucky v.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Mercer County*, wrote that a display including the Mayflower Compact, the Declaration of Independence, the Ten Commandments, Magna Carta, *The Star-Spangled Banner*, and the national motto could be erected in the Mercer County courthouse.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky has been known to have unusually high political candidacy age laws, especially compared to surrounding states.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Since the late 1990s, Kentucky has supported Republican candidates for most federal political offices, and, more recently, for state-level office as well.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The state leaned toward the Democratic Party from 1860 through the 1990s, and was considered a swing state at the presidential level for most of the latter half of the 20th century.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The southeastern region of the state aligned with the Union during the war and has consistently supported Republican candidates.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The central and western portions of the state were heavily Democratic in the years leading to the Civil War, were pro-secessionist and pro-Confederate during the Civil War, and in the decades following the war.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky was part of the Democratic Solid South in the second half of the nineteenth century and through the majority of the twentieth century.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Mirroring a broader national reversal of party composition, the Kentucky Democratic Party of the twenty-first century primarily consists of liberal whites, African Americans, and other minorities.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Although most of the state's voters have reliably elected Republican candidates for federal office since the late 1990s, Democrats held an advantage in party registration until 2022.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] From 1964 through 2004, Kentucky voted for the eventual winner of the election for President of the United States; however, in the 2008 election the state lost its bellwether status.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Republican John McCain won Kentucky, but he lost the national popular and electoral vote to Democrat Barack Obama (McCain carried Kentucky 57% to 41%).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] 116 of Kentucky's 120 counties supported former Massachusetts governor Mitt Romney in the 2012 election while he lost to Barack Obama nationwide.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Voters in the commonwealth have supported the previous three Democratic candidates elected to the White House in the late 20th century, all from Southern states: Lyndon B.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Johnson (Texas) in 1964, Jimmy Carter (Georgia) in 1976, and Bill Clinton (Arkansas) in 1992 and 1996.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In the twenty-first century presidential elections, the state has become a Republican stronghold, supporting that party's presidential candidates by double-digit margins from 2000 through 2020.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] At the same time, voters have continued to elect Democratic candidates to state and local offices in many jurisdictions.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Elliott County, Kentucky is notable for having held the longest streak of any county in the United States voting Democratic.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Founded in 1869, Elliott County supported the Democratic nominee in every presidential election from 1872 (the first in which it participated) until 2012.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In 2016, Donald Trump became the first Republican to ever carry the county, and he did so in a 44-point landslide, highlighting the modern Republican Party's dominance among rural whites and many ancestrally Democratic, socially-conservative voters.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky is one of the most anti-abortion states in the United States.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] A 2014 poll conducted by Pew Research Center found that 57% of Kentucky's population thought that abortion should be illegal in all/most cases, while only 36% thought that abortion should be legal in all/most cases.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In a 2020 study, Kentucky was ranked as the 8th hardest state for citizens to vote in.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky culture is firmly Southern, and influenced by that of Appalachia.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The state is known for bourbon and whiskey distilling, tobacco, horse racing, and college basketball.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky is more similar to the Upland South in terms of ancestry that is predominantly American.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Nevertheless, during the 19th century, Kentucky did receive a substantial number of German immigrants, who settled mostly in the Midwest and parts of the Upper South, along the Ohio River primarily in Louisville, Covington and Newport.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Only Maryland, Delaware and West Virginia have higher German ancestry percentages than Kentucky among Census-defined Southern states, although Kentucky's percentage is closer to Arkansas and Virginia's than the previously named state's percentages.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Scottish Americans, English Americans and Scotch-Irish Americans have heavily influenced Kentucky culture, and are present in every part of the state.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] As of the 1980s the only counties in the United States where more than half the population cited "English" as their only ancestry group were all in the hills of eastern Kentucky (and made up virtually every county in this region).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] While less than 8% of the total population is Black, Kentucky has a relatively significant rural African American population in the Central and Western areas of the state.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky adopted the Jim Crow system of racial segregation in most public spheres after the Civil War.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Louisville's 1914 ordinance for residential racial segregation was struck down by the Supreme Court in 1917.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] However, in 1908 Kentucky enacted the Day Law, "An Act to Prohibit White and Colored Persons from Attending the Same School", which Berea College unsuccessfully challenged at the US Supreme Court in 1908.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Johnson filed suit for admission to the University of Kentucky; as a result, nearly thirty African American students entered UK graduate and professional programs in the summer of 1949.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky integrated its schools after the 1954 *Brown v.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Board of Education* verdict, later adopting the first state civil rights act in the South in 1966.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky commemorates Confederate Memorial Day but added Juneteenth as a holiday by proclamation of Governor Andy Beshear in 2024.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The biggest day in American horse racing, the Kentucky Derby, is preceded by the two-week Derby Festival in Louisville.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The Derby Festival features many events, including Thunder Over Louisville, the Pegasus Parade, the Great Steamboat Race, Fest-a-Ville, the Chow Wagon, BalloonFest, BourbonVille, and many others leading up to the big race.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Louisville also plays host to the Kentucky State Fair and the Kentucky Shakespeare Festival.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Bowling Green, the state's third-largest city and home to the only assembly plant in the world that manufactures the Chevrolet Corvette, opened the National Corvette Museum in 1994.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The fourth-largest city, Owensboro, gives credence to its nickname of "Barbecue Capital of the World" by hosting the annual International Bar-B-Q Festival.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Old Louisville, the largest historic preservation district in the United States featuring Victorian architecture and the third largest overall, hosts the St.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] James Court Art Show, the largest outdoor art show in the United States.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The neighborhood was also home to the Southern Exposition (1883–1887), which featured the first public display of Thomas Edison's light bulb, and was the setting of Alice Hegan Rice's novel, *Mrs.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Fairview was the birthplace of Jefferson Davis, who would become President of the Confederate States of America; the town had the Jefferson Davis Memorial, a 351-foot concrete obelisk, built in 1917.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Hodgenville, the birthplace of Abraham Lincoln, hosts the annual Lincoln Days Celebration, and also hosted the kick-off for the National Abraham Lincoln Bicentennial Celebration in February 2008.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Bardstown celebrates its heritage as a major bourbon-producing region with the Kentucky Bourbon Festival.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Glasgow mimics Glasgow, Scotland by hosting the Glasgow Highland Games, its own version of the Highland Games, and Sturgis hosts "Little Sturgis", a mini version of Sturgis, South Dakota's annual Sturgis Motorcycle Rally.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The National Quilt Museum is in Paducah.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] It hosts QuiltWeek, an annual competition and celebration of that attracts artists and hobbyists from the world of quilting.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Winchester celebrates an original Kentucky creation, Beer Cheese, with its Beer Cheese Festival held annually in June.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Beer Cheese was developed in Clark County at some point in the 1940s along the Kentucky River.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The residents of tiny Benton pay tribute to their favorite tuber, the sweet potato, by hosting Tater Day.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Residents of Clarkson in Grayson County celebrate their city's ties to the honey industry by celebrating the Clarkson Honeyfest.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The Clarkson Honeyfest is held the last Thursday, Friday and Saturday in September, and is the "Official State Honey Festival of Kentucky".
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Renfro Valley, Kentucky is home to Renfro Valley Entertainment Center and the Kentucky Music Hall of Fame and is known as "Kentucky's Country Music Capital", a designation given it by the Kentucky State Legislature in the late 1980s.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The Renfro Valley Gatherin' is today America's second-oldest continually broadcast radio program of any kind.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] It is broadcast on local radio station WRVK and a syndicated network of nearly 200 other stations across the United States and Canada every week.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Contemporary Christian music star Steven Curtis Chapman is a Paducah native, and Rock and Roll Hall of Famers the Everly Brothers are closely connected with Muhlenberg County, where older brother Don was born.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Merle Travis, Country and Western artist known for both his signature "Travis picking" guitar playing style, as well as his hit song "Sixteen Tons", was also born in Muhlenberg County.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky was also home to Mildred and Patty Hill, the Louisville sisters credited with composing the tune to the ditty Happy Birthday to You in 1893; Loretta Lynn (Johnson County), Brian Littrell and Kevin Richardson of the Backstreet Boys, and Billy Ray Cyrus (Flatwoods).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] However, its depth lies in its signature sound – Bluegrass music.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Bill Monroe, "The Father of Bluegrass", was born in the small Ohio County town of Rosine, while Ricky Skaggs, Keith Whitley, David "Stringbean" Akeman, Louis Marshall "Grandpa" Jones, Sonny and Bobby Osborne, and Sam Bush (who has been compared to Monroe) all hail from Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The Bluegrass Music Hall of Fame & Museum is located in Owensboro, while the annual Festival of the Bluegrass is held in Lexington.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky was also home to famed jazz musician Lionel Hampton.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Handy and R&B singer Wilson Pickett also spent considerable time in Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The R&B group Midnight Star and Hip-Hop group Nappy Roots were both formed in Kentucky, as were country acts the Kentucky Headhunters, Montgomery Gentry, Halfway to Hazard, the Judds, and Dove Award-winning Christian groups Audio Adrenaline and Bride.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Black Stone Cherry hails from rural Edmonton.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Indie rock bands Slint, My Morning Jacket, Wax Fang, White Reaper, and Tantric formed in Louisville; indie rock bands Cage the Elephant, Sleeper Agent, and Morning Teleportation are from Bowling Green.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The bluegrass groups Driftwood and Kentucky Rain, along with Nick Lachey of the pop band 98 Degrees are also from Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] King Crimson guitarist Adrian Belew is from Covington.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Noted singer and actress Rosemary Clooney was a native of Maysville, her legacy being celebrated at the annual music festival bearing her name.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Noted songwriter and actor Will Oldham is from Louisville.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] More recently in the limelight are country artists Chris Stapleton, Sturgill Simpson, Tyler Childers, and Chris Knight.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In eastern Kentucky, old-time music carries on the tradition of ancient ballads and reels developed in historical Appalachia.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky has played a major role in Southern and American literature, producing works that often celebrate the working class, rural life, nature, and explore issues of class, extractive economy, and family.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Government's war on poverty, and others.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Author Thomas Merton lived most of his life and wrote most of his books – including *The Seven Storey Mountain* (1948), ranked on *National Review*'s list of the 100 best non-fiction books of the century – during his time as a monk at the Abbey of Our Lady of Gethsemani near Bardstown, Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Since the later part of the 20th century, several writers from Kentucky have published widely read and critically acclaimed books, including: Wendell Berry (fl.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Well-known playwrights from Kentucky include Marsha Norman (works include *'night, Mother*, 1983), Naomi Wallace (works include *One Flea Spare*, 1995), and George C.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Wolfe (works include *Jelly's Last Jam*, 1992).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky's cuisine is generally similar to and is a part of traditional southern cooking, although in some areas of the state it can blend elements of both the South and Appalachia, mixing Appalachian with the native Southern cuisine of the area.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] One original Kentucky dish is called the Hot Brown, a dish normally layered in this order: toasted bread, turkey, bacon, tomatoes and topped with mornay sauce.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] It was developed at the Brown Hotel in Louisville.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The Pendennis Club in Louisville is the birthplace of the Old Fashioned cocktail.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Also, Western Kentucky is known for its own regional style of Southern barbecue.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Central Kentucky is the birthplace of Beer Cheese.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Harland Sanders, a Kentucky colonel, originated Kentucky Fried Chicken at his service station in North Corbin, though the first franchised KFC was located in South Salt Lake, Utah.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky is the home of sports teams such as Minor League Baseball's Triple-A Louisville Bats and High-A Bowling Green Hot Rods.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] It is home to the independent Atlantic League of Professional Baseball's Lexington Legends and the Frontier League's Florence Y'alls.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The Lexington Horsemen and Louisville Fire of the now-defunct af2 had been interested in making a move up to the "major league" Arena Football League, but nothing has come of those plans.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The northern part of the state lies across the Ohio River from Cincinnati, which is home to the National Football League's Cincinnati Bengals, Major League Baseball's Cincinnati Reds.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] It is not uncommon for fans to park in the city of Newport and use the Newport Southbank Pedestrian Bridge, locally known as the "Purple People Bridge", to walk to these games in Cincinnati.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Georgetown College in Georgetown was the location for the Bengals' summer training camp, until it was announced in 2012 that the Bengals would no longer use the facilities.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] As in many states, especially those without major league professional sports teams, college athletics are prominent.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] This is especially true of the state's three Division I Football Bowl Subdivision (FBS) programs, including the Kentucky Wildcats, the Western Kentucky Hilltoppers, and the Louisville Cardinals.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The Wildcats, Hilltoppers, and Cardinals are among the most tradition-rich college men's basketball teams in the United States, combining for 11 National Championships and 24 NCAA Final Fours; all three are high on the lists of total all-time wins, wins per season, and average wins per season.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] (right) ranking 2nd and 3rd in capacity among college basketball arenas.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The Kentucky Wildcats are particularly notable, leading all Division I programs in all-time wins, win percentage, NCAA tournament appearances, and being second only to UCLA in NCAA championships.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Louisville has stepped onto the football scene, including winning the 2007 Orange Bowl as well as the 2013 Sugar Bowl, and producing 2016 Heisman Trophy winner Lamar Jackson.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Western Kentucky, the 2002 national champion in Division I-AA football (now Football Championship Subdivision (FCS)), completed its transition to Division I FBS football in 2009.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The Kentucky Derby is a horse race held annually in Louisville on the first Saturday in May.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The Valhalla Golf Club in Louisville has hosted several editions of the PGA Championship, Senior PGA Championship and Ryder Cup since the 1990s.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The NASCAR Cup Series held a race at the Kentucky Speedway in Sparta, Kentucky from 2011 to 2020.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The NASCAR Nationwide Series and the Camping World Truck Series raced there through 2020.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The IndyCar Series previously raced there as well.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Ohio Valley Wrestling in Louisville was the primary location for training and rehab for WWE professional wrestlers from 2000 until 2008, when WWE moved its contracted talent to Florida Championship Wrestling.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] OVW later became the primary developmental territory for Total Nonstop Action Wrestling (TNA) from 2011 to 2013.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In 2014 Louisville City FC, a professional soccer team in the league then known as USL Pro and now as the United Soccer League, was announced.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The team made its debut in 2015, playing home games at Louisville Slugger Field.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In its first season, Louisville City was the official reserve side for Orlando City SC, who made its debut in Major League Soccer at the same time.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] That arrangement ended in 2016 when Orlando City established a directly controlled reserve side in the USL.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In 2021, Lexington SC was founded as a professional soccer team out of Lexington, competing in USL League One.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] They played their home games at Toyota Stadium until construction on Lexington SC Stadium was completed in 2024.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] In 2025, they joined the USL Championship league.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The club has companion women's teams that compete in the USL W League and USL Super League.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The distinction of being named a **Kentucky colonel** is the highest title of honor bestowed by the Commonwealth of Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Commissions for Kentucky colonels are given by the Governor and the Secretary of State to individuals in recognition of noteworthy accomplishments and outstanding service to a community, state or the nation.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] The sitting governor of the Commonwealth of Kentucky bestows the honor of a colonel's commission, by issuance of letters patent.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/kentucky-p02] Kentucky colonels are commissioned for life and act officially as the state's goodwill ambassadors.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-baseball-park] The field was located within a large block bounded by 4th Street (east); Hill Street (south); 6th Street (west); and Magnolia Avenue (north).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-baseball-park] The block was across the street to the south of Central Park, which still exists, and was also adjacent to a field used by the amateur Louisville Eagles.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-baseball-park] A few years after the breakup of the club following the 1877 Louisville Grays scandal, the large block was redeveloped for other purposes.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-baseball-park] It was the home of the Southern Exposition from 1883 through 1887.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-baseball-park] By the 1890s, the large block had been cut into lots and developed into an upper-class neighborhood known as St.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-grays] The **Louisville Grays** were a 19th-century United States baseball team and charter member of the National League, based in Louisville, Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-grays] They played two seasons, 1876 and 1877, and compiled a record of 65–61.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-grays] Their home games were at the Louisville Baseball Park.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-grays] The Grays were owned by businessman Walter Newman Haldeman, owner and publisher of the *Louisville Courier-Journal* newspaper.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-grays] The Grays were undone by Major League Baseball's first gambling scandal.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-grays] The team was in first place in August 1877, then suddenly lost seven games and tied one against the Boston Red Stockings and Hartford Dark Blues.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-grays] Boston ended up winning the pennant, seven games ahead of the second-place Grays.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-grays] A *Courier-Journal* story questioning the team's conduct was written by John Haldeman, the owner's son.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-grays] Team president Charles Chase received two anonymous telegrams.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-grays] One noted that gamblers were favoring the less talented Hartford team in an upcoming series.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-grays] The second telegram predicted Louisville would throw the next game versus Hartford on August 21.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-grays] The Grays committed a number of suspicious errors and lost that game 7–0.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-grays] League president William Hulbert investigated and ordered players to authorize Western Union to release all telegrams sent or received during the 1877 season.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-grays] All players complied except shortstop Bill Craver, the team's captain.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-grays] The telegrams indicated that pitcher Jim Devlin, left fielder George Hall, and utility player Al Nichols intentionally lost games in exchange for money.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-grays] No direct evidence was found implicating Craver.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-grays] All four were banned from baseball for life, Craver for refusing to comply with the investigation.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-grays] Devlin pitched every inning for the 1877 Grays, leading the league in games and innings pitched.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-grays] Hall played every inning in left field; he was a good batter, and was the 1876 home run leader with five.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-grays] Louis Brown Stockings had signed Devlin and Hall for 1878 and went out of business with the Grays after the investigation.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Since 2003, Louisville and Jefferson County have shared the same borders following a city-county merger.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The consolidated government is officially called the Louisville/Jefferson County Metro Government, commonly known as Louisville Metro.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The term "Jefferson County" is still used in some contexts, especially for incorporated cities outside the "balance" area that defines Louisville proper.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The total population of the consolidated area was 782,969 at the 2020 census, while the balance area (excluding other incorporated cities) had a population of 633,045 and is often cited in national statistics.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The Louisville metropolitan area, which includes 12 surrounding counties in Kentucky and Southern Indiana, has 1.39 million residents and is the 43rd-largest metropolitan area in the U.S.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Named after King Louis XVI of France, Louisville was founded in 1778 by George Rogers Clark, making it one of the oldest cities west of the Appalachians.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] With the nearby Falls of the Ohio as the only major obstruction to river traffic between the upper Ohio River and the Gulf of Mexico, the settlement first grew as a portage site.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] It was the founding city of the Louisville and Nashville Railroad, which grew into a 6,000-mile (9,700 km) system across 13 states.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Today, the city is known as the home of boxer Muhammad Ali, the Kentucky Derby, Kentucky Fried Chicken, the University of Louisville and its Cardinals, Louisville Slugger baseball bats, and *Fortune* 500 company Humana, BrightSpring Health Services and Yum!
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Louisville Muhammad Ali International Airport, the city's main commercial airport, hosts UPS's worldwide hub.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The correct pronunciation of the name of *Louisville* is hotly debated.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] All three are generally considered acceptable; the Louisville Visitor Center says that only the rare /ˈluːɪsvɪl/ ⓘ *LOO-iss-vil* is completely unacceptable (though it is the correct pronunciation for the names of several minor cities with that name).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] There are also acceptable hybrid ways of saying the name, such as /ˈluːəvɪl/ *LOO-ə-vil*, a mixture of the first and second pronunciations.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The *LOO-ə-vəl* pronunciation is the dominant local pronunciation.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Some even refer to it as the "only" correct way to pronounce the name of the city.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] *LOO-ee-vil*, while respecting the proper pronunciation of the name of the French king who gave Louisville its name, is significantly less common among locals.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] It is, however, frequently used by those not from the area.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] In 2001, local journalist and historian George H.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Yater noted that older natives tended toward the second pronunciation, and that both the first and second pronunciations were used equally in local radio and television broadcasting; however, new personalities were taught that the first one was "correct".
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The history of Louisville spans hundreds of years, and has been influenced by the area's geography and proximity to the Falls of the Ohio River.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Since the Falls created a barrier to river travel, settlements grew at this portage point.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The first European settlement in the vicinity of modern-day Louisville was on Corn Island in 1778 by Col.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] George Rogers Clark, credited as the founder of Louisville.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Several landmarks in the community are named after him.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Two years later, in 1780, the Virginia General Assembly approved the town charter of Louisville.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The city was named in honor of King Louis XVI of France, whose soldiers were then aiding Americans in the Revolutionary War.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Early residents lived in forts to protect themselves from raids from the local indigenous population, but they moved out by the late 1780s.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] In 1803, explorers Meriwether Lewis and William Clark organized their expedition across America in the town of Clarksville, Indiana at the present-day Falls of the Ohio opposite Louisville, Kentucky.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The city's early growth was influenced by the fact that river boats had to be unloaded and moved downriver before reaching the falls.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] By 1828, the population had grown to 7,000 and Louisville became an incorporated city.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Early Louisville was a major shipping port and enslaved African Americans worked in a variety of associated trades.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The city was often a point of escape for fugitive slaves to the north, as Indiana was a free state.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] During this point in the 1850s, the city was growing and vibrant, but that also came with negativity.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] It was the center of planning, supplies, recruiting, and transportation for numerous campaigns, especially in the Western Theater.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Ethnic tensions rose, and on August 6, 1855, known as "Bloody Monday", Protestant mobs attacked German and Irish Catholic neighborhoods on election day, resulting in 22 deaths and widespread property damage.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Then by 1861, the civil war had broken out.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] During the Civil War, Louisville was a major stronghold of Union forces, which kept Kentucky firmly in the Union.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] By the end of the war, the city of Louisville itself had not been attacked, although skirmishes and battles, including the battles of Perryville and Corydon, took place nearby.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] After the war, returning Confederate veterans largely took political control of the city, leading to the saying that Louisville joined the Confederacy after the war was over.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The first Kentucky Derby was held on May 17, 1875, at the Louisville Jockey Club track (later renamed Churchill Downs).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The Derby was originally shepherded by Meriwether Lewis Clark Jr., the grandson of William Clark of the Lewis and Clark Expedition, and grandnephew of the city's founder George Rogers Clark.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Horse racing had a strong tradition in Kentucky, whose Inner Bluegrass Region had been a center of breeding high-quality livestock throughout the 19th century.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Ten thousand spectators watched the first Derby, which Aristides won.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] On March 27, 1890, the city was devastated and its downtown nearly destroyed when what scientists now estimate was an F4 tornado tore through as part of the middle Mississippi Valley tornado outbreak.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] It is estimated that between 74 and 120 people were killed and 200 were injured.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The damage cost the city $2.5 million (equivalent to $69 million in 2019).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Established in 1896, Neighborhood House Louisville was the first settlement movement house in the state.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Following the Civil War and the Emancipation Proclamation, freed slaves settled in a neighborhood of Louisville called Little Africa, nicknamed "the gateway to the South", near the present neighborhood of Park DuValle.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The neighborhood was described as a "thriving community" by the 1920s, and declined between the 1940s and 1950s.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] In 1914, the city of Louisville passed a racially based residential zoning code, following Baltimore, Atlanta, and a handful of cities in the Carolinas.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The NAACP challenged the ordinance in two cases.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Two weeks after the ordinance was enacted, an African-American named Arthur Harris moved into a house on a block designated for whites.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The second case was planned to create a test case.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] William Warley, the president of the local chapter of the NAACP, tendered a purchase offer on a white block from Charles Buchanan, a white real estate agent.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Warley also wrote a letter declaring his intention to build a house on that lot and reside there.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] With the understanding that the Louisville ordinance made it illegal for him to live there, Warley withheld payment, setting in motion a breach of contract suit by Buchanan.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Supreme Court agreed to hear the case of *Buchanan v.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The court struck down the Louisville residential segregation ordinance, ruling that it violated the Fourteenth Amendment's due process clause.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] In 1917, shortly after the United States' entry into World War I, Louisville was selected as the site of Camp Zachary Taylor.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Camp Taylor was one of the country's largest World War I training camps.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] It was home of the 84th Infantry Division and trained over 150,000 men by the end of war, including F.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Many of the buildings and infrastructure in the Camp Taylor neighborhood of Louisville are there as a result of the training camp.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] In 1929, Louisville completed the lock and dam in the Falls of the Ohio and the city began referring to itself as "where Northern enterprise and Southern hospitality meet".
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Between the industrial boom of that year and through the Great Depression, Louisville gained 15,000 new residents, about 3% of them black, most fleeing poverty in rural areas.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Throughout January 1937, 19.17 inches (48.7 cm) of rain fell in Louisville, and by January 27, the Ohio River crested at a record 57.15 feet (17.42 m), almost 30 feet (9.1 m) above flood stage.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] These events triggered the "Great Flood of 1937", which lasted into early February.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The flood submerged 60–70 percent of the city, caused complete loss of power for four days, and forced the evacuation of 175,000 or 230,000 residents, depending on sources.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] 90 people died as a result of the flood.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] This led to dramatic changes in where residents lived.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] After the flood, the areas of high elevation in the eastern part of the city had decades of residential growth.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Today, the city is protected by numerous flood walls.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Louisville was a center for factory war production during World War II.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] In May 1942, the U.S. government assigned the Curtiss-Wright Aircraft Company, a war plant located at Louisville's air field, for wartime aircraft production.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The factory produced the C-46 Commando cargo plane, among other aircraft.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] In 1946, the factory was sold to International Harvester, which began large-scale production of tractors and agricultural equipment.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] In 1950, the Census Bureau reported Louisville's population as 84.3% white and 15.6% black.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Throughout the 1940s, Louisville had more black police officers than any other Southern city, though they were allowed to patrol only black districts.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] This, in part, made Louisville seem like a more racially progressive city than other Southern cities, although only when black citizens accepted a lower status than white citizens.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Many historians have referred to this "veil" of segregation as a "polite" racism.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Historian George Wright stated that polite racism "often deluded both blacks and well-meaning whites into believing that real progress was being made in their city".
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] For example, in the city Jim Crow practices were not maintained by law so much as by custom.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Similar to many other older American cities, Louisville began to experience a movement of people and businesses to the suburbs in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Middle class residents used newly built freeways and interstate highways to commute to work, moving into more distant but newer housing.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Because of tax laws, businesses found it cheaper to build new rather than renovate older buildings.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Economic changes included a decline in local manufacturing.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The West End and older areas of the South End, in particular, began to decline economically as many local factories closed.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] In 1974, a major (F4) tornado hit Louisville as part of the 1974 Super Outbreak of tornadoes that struck 13 states.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] It covered 21 miles (34 km) and destroyed several hundred homes in the Louisville area, causing two deaths.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Since the 1980s, many of the city's urban neighborhoods have been revitalized into areas popular with young professionals and college students.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The greatest change has occurred along the Bardstown Road/Baxter Avenue and Frankfort Avenue corridors as well as the Old Louisville neighborhood.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] In recent years, such change has also occurred in the East Market District (NuLu).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Since the late 1990s, Downtown has experienced significant residential, tourist and retail growth.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Major new sports complexes built include KFC Yum!
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Center (2010), Louisville Slugger Field (2000), and Lynn Family Stadium (2020).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] On March 13, 2020, four plainclothed officers from Louisville Metro Police Department executed a "no-knock" search warrant which led to the killing of Breonna Taylor, a 26-year-old African-American woman.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] For months afterward, Taylor's family, members of the local community, and people around the world protested to demand that officers involved in the shooting be fired and criminally charged.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] These protests and demonstrations coincided and intertwined with the international George Floyd protests, as well as the Black Lives Matter movement and a broader movement of racial unrest.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] As a result of the incident, the police chief was fired and four officers received federal charges, but no significant systemic changes were made.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] On April 10, 2023, a mass shooting occurred at the Old National Bank, killing five people, and injuring nine others.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The suspect, who was a bank employee and who officials said was livestreaming the rampage, was killed by the police after exchanging fire with them.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] On November 4, 2025, a McDonnell Douglas MD-11 cargo plane operating as UPS Airlines Flight 2976 crashed shortly after takeoff from Louisville Muhammad Ali International Airport, killing 14 people, injuring 15, and igniting a large fire.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Several buildings near the airport, including a petroleum recycling center, were struck or set on fire.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The cause of the crash is under investigation.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The five-year Southern Exposition in Louisville, the second-largest American exhibition to date in 1883, had the largest to-date installation of light bulbs by their recent inventor and then-former resident Thomas Edison.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Louisville also established the first free public library in the US to be staffed by and provide services exclusively for African Americans in 1905.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Medical advances in Louisville include the first human hand transplant in the US in 1999 and the first self-contained artificial heart transplant in 2001.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Louisville and Jefferson County have a combined area of 397.68 square miles (1,030.0 km2), of which 380.46 square miles (985.4 km2) is land and 17.23 square miles (44.6 km2) (4.33%) is covered by water.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Louisville is southeasterly situated along the border between Kentucky and Indiana, the Ohio River, in north-central Kentucky at the Falls of the Ohio.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Louisville is an Upper South city located in a Southern state that is influenced by both Southern and Midwestern culture.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] It is sometimes referred to as either one of the northernmost Southern cities or as one of the southernmost Northern cities in the United States.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Louisville is located in Kentucky's outer Bluegrass region.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Its development has been influenced by its location on the Ohio River, which spurred Louisville's growth from an isolated camp site into a major shipping port.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Much of the city is located on a very wide and flat floodplain surrounded by hill country on all sides.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Much of the area was swampland that had to be drained as the city grew.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] In the 1840s, most creeks were rerouted or placed in canals to prevent flooding and disease outbreaks.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Areas generally east of I-65 are above the flood plain, and are composed of gently rolling hills.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The southernmost parts of Jefferson County are in the scenic and largely undeveloped Knobs region, which is home to Jefferson Memorial Forest.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The Louisville-Jefferson County, KY-IN Metropolitan Statistical Area (MSA), the 43rd largest in the United States, includes the Kentucky county of Jefferson (coterminous with Louisville Metro), plus twelve outlying counties—seven in Kentucky and five in Southern Indiana.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Louisville's MSA is included in the Louisville–Elizabethtown–Madison, KY–IN Combined Statistical Area (CSA), which also includes the Elizabethtown, KY MSA, as well as the Madison, IN Micropolitan Statistical Area.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The downtown business district of Louisville is located immediately south of the Ohio River and southeast of the Falls of the Ohio.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Major roads extend outwards from the downtown area in all directions.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The airport is about 6.75 miles (10.86 km) south of the downtown area.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The industrial sections of town are to the south and west of the airport, while most of the residential areas of the city are to the southwest, south, and east of downtown.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Twelve of the 15 buildings in Kentucky over 300 feet (91 m) are located in downtown Louisville.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Another primary business and industrial district is located in the suburban area east of the city on Hurstbourne Parkway.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Louisville's late 19th- and early 20th-century development was spurred by three large suburban parks built at the edges of the city in 1890.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The city's architecture is a blend of old and new.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The Old Louisville neighborhood is the largest historic preservation district solely featuring Victorian homes and buildings in the United States; it is also the third-largest district containing such architectural distinctions in the United States.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Many modern skyscrapers are located downtown, as well as older preserved structures, such as the Southern National Bank building.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The buildings of West Main Street in downtown Louisville have the largest collection of cast iron facades of anywhere outside of New York's SoHo neighborhood.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Since the mid-20th century, Louisville has in some ways been divided into three sides of town: the West End, the South End, and the East End.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Nevertheless, he says the perception is still strong.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The South End has long had a reputation as a white, working-class part of town, while the East End has been seen as middle and upper class.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] According to the Greater Louisville Association of Realtors, the area with the lowest median home sales price is west of Interstate 65, in the West and South Ends.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The middle range of home sales prices are between Interstates 64 and 65 in the South and East Ends, and the highest median home sales price are north of Interstate 64 in the East End.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Immigrants from Southeast Asia tend to settle in the South End, while immigrants from Eastern Europe settle in the East End.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Louisville has a humid subtropical climate (Köppen *Cfa*), typical of the Upper South, and is located in USDA plant hardiness zone 7a.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Springlike conditions typically begin in mid-to-late March, summer from mid-to-late-May to late September, with fall in the October–November period.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Seasonal extremes in both temperature and precipitation are not uncommon during early spring and late fall; severe weather is not uncommon, with occasional tornado outbreaks in the region.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Winter typically brings a mix of rain, sleet, and snow, with occasional heavy snowfall and icing.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Louisville averages 4.5 days with low temperatures dipping to 10 °F (−12 °C); the first and last freezes of the season on average fall on November 2 and April 5, respectively.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Summer is typically hazy, hot, and humid with long periods of 90–100 °F (32–38 °C) temperatures and drought conditions at times.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Louisville averages 38 days a year with high temperatures at or above 90 °F (32 °C).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The mean annual temperature is 58.2 °F (14.6 °C), with an average annual snowfall of 12.7 inches (32 cm) and an average annual rainfall of 44.9 inches (1,140 mm).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The wettest seasons are spring and summer, although rainfall is fairly constant year round.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] During the winter, particularly in January and February, several days of snow can be expected.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] January is the coldest month, with a mean temperature of 34.9 °F (1.6 °C).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] July is the average hottest month with a mean of 79.3 °F (26.3 °C).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The highest recorded temperature was 107 °F (42 °C), which last occurred on July 14, 1936, and the lowest recorded temperature was −22 °F (−30 °C) on January 19, 1994.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] In 2012, Louisville had the fourth-hottest summer on record, with the temperature rising up to 106 °F (41 °C) in July and the June all-time monthly record high temperature being broken on two consecutive days.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] As the city exemplifies the urban heat island effect, temperatures in commercial areas and in the industrialized areas along interstates are often higher than in the suburbs, often as much as 5 °F (2.8 °C).
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Between 1970 and 2000, Louisville lost population each decade.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] As of the 2000 census, Louisville had a population of 256,231, down from the 1990 census population of 269,063.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Due to the city-county merger that occurred in 2003, which expanded the city limits, the city's population increased to 597,337 at the 2010 census count.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Louisville is the largest city in Kentucky, with 17.1% of the state's total population as of 2010; the balance's percentage was 13.8%.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The 2007 demographic breakdown for the entire Louisville Metro area was 74.8% White (71.7% non-Hispanic), 22.2% African American, 0.6% Native American, 2.0% Asian, 0.1% Hawaiian or Pacific islander, 1.4% other, and 1.6% multiracial.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] About 2.9% of the total population was identified as Hispanic of any race.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] During the same year, the area of premerger Louisville consisted 60.1% White, 35.2% African American, 1.9% Asian, 0.2% Native American, and 3.0% other, with 2.4% identified as Hispanic of any race.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Of the 287,012 households, 29.6% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 45.2% were married couples living together, 14.7% had a female householder with no husband present, and 36.2% were not families.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] About 30.5% of all households were made up of individuals, and 10.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The average household size was 2.37 and the average family size was 2.97.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] For every 100 females, there were 91.60 males.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 87.60 males.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The median income for a household in 2017 was $51,960.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] For non-family households the median income was $32,446, and for family households was $67,965.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] In 2017, males had a median income of $36,326 while females had a median income of $30,464.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] The latest available data for per capita income comes from 2006, and was $23,304 for the county.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] About 9.5% of families and 15.1% of the population were below the poverty line in 2017, including 23.5% of those under age 18 and 8.2% of those ages 65 or over.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Additionally, around 60,000 Cuban Americans are said to live in the Louisville area, with Jefferson County ranking 12th nationally.
[src:louisville-baseball-park/louisville-kentucky-p01] Louisville hosts religious institutions of various faiths, including Christianity, Judaism, Islam, Hinduism, Buddhism, Sikhism and the Baháʼí Faith.
